<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military, Nuclear &amp; Space Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Shows `Deep Understanding' of Nuclear Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Shows `Deep Understanding' of Nuclear Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK2306070094 Moscow SEGODNYA in Russian 23 Jun 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> MK2306070094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow SEGODNYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Pavel Felgengauer in the "Defense" column: </F>
"Russian Nuclear Triad Ready for Action. President Yeltsin 
Presses `Red Button' for First Time"] 
  [Text] The latest annual command staff exercise on control 
of the Russian Federation Strategic Nuclear Forces, held 21-22 
June at the Russian Army General Staff with the participation of 
the main staffs of the Navy, the Air Force, and the Strategic 
Missile Forces (the sea, air, and ground components of the 
strategic nuclear triad), differed markedly from the previous 
ones. Chief of General Staff Mikhail Kolesnikov told SEGODNYA's 
correspondent that for the first time the country's top civilian 
official -- the supreme commander (the president) -- personally 
directed the national Strategic Nuclear Forces. This is without 
precedent in the entire existence of Soviet nuclear weapons. 
  On the morning of 22 June -- a notable day in Russia's 
history -- during the final stage of the exercise, Boris Yeltsin 
arrived at the General Staff accompanied by his national 
security adviser Yuriy Baturin and, according to General 
Kolesnikov, "personally exercised control" from the General 
Staff Central Command Post. According to the military, "the 
president showed a deep understanding on matters of the control 
of strategic forces and issued guidance on improving the 
Strategic Nuclear Forces taking into account the bilateral 
agreements with the United States and Great Britain on missile 
retargeting." 
  Then the president returned to the Kremlin, canceling a 
scheduled meeting with the press, so his personal impressions 
about how the famous nuclear button operates remain unknown to 
the broad public. Meanwhile, the country's top military 
leadership went to "a command post at one branch of the armed 
forces to rehearse one element," and with that the training 
session was successfully concluded. 
  According to the chief of General Staff, the exercise showed 
that the Russian Federation nuclear triad and early warning 
system are "ready to address the tasks assigned in accordance 
with existing regulations." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

