<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military, Nuclear &amp; Space Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Start' Conversion Missile To Be Tested </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Start' Conversion Missile To Be Tested </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2306131994 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0815 
GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2306131994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Anatoliy Yurkin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 23 Jun -- Preparations for the launch of a 
"Start" missile within a conversion program for the use of 
weapons systems for peaceful purposes have started. The 
preparations are under way at the state test range of strategic 
missile troops in Mirnyy, Arkhangel Oblast. In an exclusive 
interview with an ITAR- TASS correspondent, Lieutenant General 
Yuriy Zhuravlev, head of the test range, said that henceforth 
"Topol" missiles would not be destroyed after their service 
life. According to him, after modification at the factory, each 
system will be used for placing non-military satellites into 
near-earth orbit. 
  Using extra-budgetary funds, enterprises of the defense 
complex have carried out experimental and design work to improve 
"Topol" specifications and presented an experimental specimen 
for tests at the state test range of strategic missile troops. 
In Gen. Zhuravlev's view, a new rocket, named "Start," has been 
developed. It has a strictly peaceful purpose promising great 
economic benefits to Russia. Contracts for launching 
communications satellites, worth many millions, have already 
been signed with South Africa and other countries. 
  In Gen. Zhuravlev's view, the "Start" can put satellites in 
orbit from anywhere in the world. Its movable platform and 
control block can be carried by different transport vehicles. 
Preparations for a launch take no more than several minutes. 
After test range trials the "Start" will put a satellite in 
orbit, and this will be the first step in using the famous 
"Topol" system for peaceful purposes. The launch is to take 
place somewhere in September, and in the meantime preparations 
for using this unique Russian missile system in a new role are 
in full swing, Lt.-Gen. Zhuravlev said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

