<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-122 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  23 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Tajikistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Talks `Proceeding Extremely Slowly' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Talks `Proceeding Extremely Slowly' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2306122994 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0930 
GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2306122994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Oleg Kuzmin] </F>
  [Text] Tehran, 23 Jun -- The discussion of individual 
points of the cease-fire agreement is proceeding extremely 
slowly. The draft of the agreement was proposed by Romero 
Piriz-Ballon, special envoy of the UN secretary general in 
Tajikistan during the second round of the Tajik talks in the 
Iranian capital. The ITAR-TASS correspondent has learned this 
from well-informed sources. 
  One of the leaders of the Tajik Islamic opposition, Haji 
Akbar Turajonzoda --who is in Tehran at present but is not 
directly involved in the talks -- explained the views of the 
government opposition in an interview with ABRAR newspaper. The 
opposition believes, he said, that the cease-fire must be 
temporary and limited and must last just for the duration of the 
talks, that is, until 27 June. Dushanbe does want a prolonged 
cease-fire, because this would be in the interests of the 
government. The fact is that, during the summer season the 
units of the opposition forces want to bring their forces into 
action. 
  Taking this into account the cease-fire would cause great 
damage to a number of the opposition's demands: The liberation 
of the arrested opposition activists, the removal of the ban on 
activities of the political parties, and the closure of criminal 
proceedings instituted against their representatives. In 
addition, the cease-fire must be abided by not only on the 
Tajik-afghan border but also on the whole of the territory of 
the republic. The government and Russian troops must renounce 
warfare methods with the opposition under the pretext of its 
desire to combat crime. It is also necessary that these troops 
should not leave their bases. 
  Despite all the obstacles, the opposition leader stressed, 
we 
want the talks to be successful. Because that is in the 
interests of the Tajik people. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-41421 </DOCNO>
