<F P=100> Tajikistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Military Condemns `Terrorist Attack' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russian Military Condemns `Terrorist Attack' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2406094494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0908 GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2406094494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Galina Gridneva] </F>
  [Text] Dushanbe June 24 TASS -- The Friday attack on a bus 
with children of Russian military serving in Tajikistan was "a 
planned terrorist act" and a "continuation of the well-planned 
and controlled terror against Russian troops deployed in 
Tajikistan," according to Vladimir Novikov, deputy commander of 
the Russian frontier troops in the Central Asian republic. 
  Several Russian military have fallen victim to the terrorist 
campaign only in the first four days of June. The latest attack 
on the bus with some 30 kids and their parents did not harm any 
of the passengers, however a passer-by was killed and several 
others wounded. Unknown gunmen fired a grenade on the bus early 
on Friday. 
  Novikov told reporters that Russian troops will mount 
protection of their personnel by seting up additional guarding 
posts and patrols in places where Russian servicemen live. He 
added that armoured vehicles will be used for protection. 
  Novikov stressed that the leadership of the Russian frontier 
troops in Tajikistan is preparing a statement in connection with 
the attack on the bus. 
  Russian border guards defend the Tajik-Afghan border to cut 
short the infiltration of armed Tajik opposition militants from 
Afghanistan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

