<H3> <TI>   President Welcomes Russia Joining Partnership for Peace </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President Welcomes Russia Joining Partnership for Peace </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2206202594 Vilnius Radio Vilnius in English in Lithuanian 
1900 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2206202594 </F>
<F P=104>  Vilnius Radio Vilnius </F>
<F P=105>  English </F><F P=105> Lithuanian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Lithuania has welcomed Russia's joining the NATO 
Partnership for Peace plan. Lithuanian President Algirdas 
Brazauskas says in his 22 June statement that it's an important 
step in the strengthening of security in Europe based on 
cooperation and partnership, as well as new democratic relations 
on the continent. We hope that will help Central Europe, 
including the Baltic states, integrate into NATO, reads the 
statement of the Lithuanian president. 
  Mr. Brazauskas says Lithuania approves of NATO's initiative 
to take on a new role in stepping up security and stability in 
the region. According to the statement, Russia's step towards 
NATO means it will not be isolated in this process and no new 
military borders will be drawn in Europe. 

