<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Radioactive Substances Smuggled Throughout Territory </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Radioactive Substances Smuggled Throughout Territory </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2306135494 Chisinau BASAPRESS in English 1945 GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2306135494 </F>
<F P=104>  Chisinau BASAPRESS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Chisinau BASAPRESS, 21/6/1994 -- Last week a group 
of smugglers of radioactive substances was arrested in action, 
announced to BASAPRESS the chief of the Moldovan Ministry of 
Interior Department for Combating Organized Crime. The group 
had been monitored by the interior ministry bodies over four 
months. Moldovan citizens Ion Petcu, Alexandru Budoianu, and 
Simion Tarlev, in collaboration with a Russian citizen, were 
attempting to sell for $20,000 a tank with 1 kg of the 
radioactive substance called Gamma Cobalt-60 to a foreign 
merchant. According to the experts, this quantity would have 
been sufficient to pollute the entire territory of Moldova. 
Simion Lacramioara, the chief of the mentioned department, 
declared that recently Moldova has faced an increase in the 
smuggling of radioactive substances and drugs. In his opinion, 
this trend is caused by the lack of strict customs controls on 
the western borders to Romania and by the lack of borders 
themselves in the east, with Ukraine. According to Lacramioara, 
the radioactive substances are stolen from Russian military 
bases and then smuggled into Western Europe. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

