<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kremlin Source: Yeltsin May Seek Extension of Term </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kremlin Source: Yeltsin May Seek Extension of Term </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2406143394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1348 GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2406143394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A high-placed source in the Moscow Kremlin told 
Interfax President Yeltsin could call a nationwide referendum in 
the hope of having his term in office extended. Addressing 
Vladimir Shumeyko's suggestion for an extension, for another two 
years, of both the president's and parliament's mandates, the 
anonymous source said Yeltsin stood the best chance to win 
presidential elections in 1996 and would be unlikely to allow 
the State Duma and Federation Council decide how long he was to 
stay in office. 
  But, the source admitted that Shumeyko's initiative was 
logical and made sense. It would allow the mostly newcomer 
politicians to learn what was what and concentrate on law-making. 
  The source said Shumeyko's initiative was a touchstone and 
the Administration's response to it would depend on whether it 
was endorsed by the lawmakers, leading political parties and 
movements and other influential forces. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

