<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rybkin Denies Supporting Shumeyko on Deputies' Powers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rybkin Denies Supporting Shumeyko on Deputies' Powers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2206202094 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1734 
GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2206202094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, 22 June -- In an interview for the "Details" 
program on Russian television this evening Federation Council 
Chairman Vladimir Shumeyko said that "he had spoken about" the 
question of extending the powers of deputies "a month and a half 
ago with both the president and with State Duma Chairman Ivan 
Rybkin." "We came to an understanding on this question, and in 
principal there were no objections either from the president or 
from the State Duma chairman," he said. 
  "Two years is a very short time for deputies to `get into' 
normal legislative work," was how Vladimir Shumeyko explained 
his position. 
  For his part, State Duma Chairman Ivan Rybkin in fact denied 
Vladimir Shumeyko's statement that the State Duma chairman had 
agreed with his proposal. In an interview with "Details" he 
said that the extension of the powers "should still be put to 
the people." "I think the Russian electorate thinks 
differently, and perhaps one ought to move toward re-election 
next year," he said. In his opinion, "considering the people's 
bitter experience, people of a quite different direction could 
be elected." 
  "It is possible to extend powers in a stable situation when 
the policy of those who carried it out has been fully 
justified," believes Gennadiy Zyuganov, leader of Russia's 
communists. "In the present situation, when the policy has 
become completely bankrupt, when the socio-economic situation 
reminds one more and more of genocide and catastrophe, and when 
the spiritual disintegration of society has reached an 
unprecedented level, the question of changing course and 
changing those who are in charge has not only ripened but has 
overripened," he told a correspondent with the "Details" program. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

