<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Chernomyrdin U.S. Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on Chernomyrdin U.S. Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Statement on Trip Results </H4>

<F P=102> LD2506164894 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1535 
GMT 25 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2506164894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Gennadiy Yezhov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 25 Jun -- The main result of the trip to the 
United States by Viktor Chernomyrdin, head of the Russian 
Government, was the achievement of fundamental accords on the 
cancellation of the discriminatory Jackson-Vanik Amendment and 
the reforming of the Coordinating Committee for Multilateral 
Export Controls by Russia's participation. This was said today 
by Viktor Chernomyrdin at Vnukovo-2 airport on his return from 
the United States. 
  In all, the work of the Gore-Chernomyrdin intergovernmental 
commission resulted, the Russian prime minister said, in the 
signing of 22 documents on technical cooperation, including in 
the joint conquest of space. Russia signed space contracts 
worth in all 200 million dollars. In addition, four agreements 
were signed with the World Bank on the provision of credits 
totalling 500 million dollars for road construction and 
agricultural support. 
  In effect, Viktor Chernomyrdin stressed, it was a beginning 
of a breakthrough toward the practical side of Russia's 
cooperation with U.S. partners. 
  Viktor Chernomyrdin pointed at a close link between the 
results of his visit to the United States and Russian President 
Boris Yeltsin's visit to the island of Corfu, where Russia had 
signed a document of cooperation with the European Community. 
"From talking about cooperation we have now come really close 
to specific actions," Viktor Chernomyrdin said. "During my 
meeting with Clinton we managed to consolidate the results 
achieved by the Gore- Chernomyrdin commission." In his view, 
all the conditions are now in place for the upcoming G-7 meeting 
in Naples, which is to be attended by President Boris Yeltsin, 
to end in a transformation of the G-7 into a G-8. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

