<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moscow Opposes Public Argument With U.S. on Chemical Arms </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Moscow Opposes Public Argument With U.S. on Chemical Arms </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2406120094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1128 GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2406120094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Aleksey Berezhkov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 24 TASS -- "We are against entering into 
polemic in public about vaguenesses which can naturally arise 
during the exchange of chemical arms data between Russia and the 
United States," a high-ranking spokesman for the Russian Foreign 
Ministry told ITAR-TASS on Friday in response to a request to 
comment on remarks by CIA Director James Woolsey, who told U.S. 
congressional hearings about the U.S. Administration's "serious 
concern" at Russia-provided data on her chemical weapons. 
  "We also have serious questions as regards data provided by 
the Americans. We hope to clear the matters up with the U.S. 
side during subsequent contacts," emphasised the spokesman who 
requested anonymity. 
  Russia and the United States have created a 
confidence-building mechanism as regards chemical arms on a 
bilateral basis. The mechanism is in operation and provides for 
exchanges of data on the military-chemical capabilities of the 
sides and for consultations should questions arise, the Russian 
Foreign Ministry spokesman said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-41461 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov123_a_94014" </HT>


