<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Soskovets Promises Better Climate for Foreign Investors </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Soskovets Promises Better Climate for Foreign Investors </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK2506113094 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 25 Jun 94 
p 2 </F>

<F P=103> MK2506113094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Sergey Rybak report under the "Investment" rubric: "Oleg </F>
Soskovets Trying To Lure Foreign Investors"] 
  [Text] At a meeting of the World Economic Forum, which 
ended its work in Moscow yesterday, First Deputy Prime Minister 
Oleg Soskovets called for foreign investors to step up their 
operations in Russia. According to government estimates, 
currently there are 1,316 -- mostly small -- joint ventures 
operating in Russia. The aggregate foreign share in them is 
estimated at $181 million. 
  The first deputy prime minister's statement was designed to 
attract as many foreign investors as possible to the Russian 
economy. In his words, Western investors will soon have an 
easier time doing business in Russia. This will be helped by 
the passing of the law "On Concession Agreements, Agreements on 
Providing Services, and Production-Sharing Agreements with 
Foreign Investors" and also by amending the law "On Foreign 
Investment in the RSFSR." According to Mr. Soskovets, these 
draft documents will shortly be considered by the Government 
Presidium. Overseas investors' operations will also by 
facilitated by presidential edicts that will form a third 
package. 
  In addition, the first deputy prime minister thought it 
"advisable to reduce the number of taxes, to cut the value-added 
tax and profit tax rates for enterprises producing goods and 
services" at the expense of raising taxes levied on mediatory 
organizations. Presently a government commission is being set up 
to improve tax legislation, which will be made up of 
representatives of federal authorities, economic institutes, and 
"prominent economic managers." 
  Oleg Soskovets expects to receive long-term loans for social 
projects from the World Bank. In his words, "Western assistance 
is necessary if reform is to succeed in a swifter and less 
painful fashion." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

