<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hata Resignation Not To Affect Relations With Japan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hata Resignation Not To Affect Relations With Japan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2506113794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1130 GMT 25 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2506113794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Vladimir Solntsev] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 25 TASS -- A decision, announced by 
Japanese Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata on Saturday, to resign 
together with the entire cabinet "will not affect the 
development of Russo-Japanese relations", a high-ranking staff 
member of the Russian Foreign Ministry, who requested anonymity, 
told ITAR-TASS on Saturday. 
  The current developments in the Japanese political life are 
an internal affair of Japan and the choice of its people, the 
diplomat said. 
  As far as Moscow's approach to relations with Japan is 
concerned, the strategic policy line, determined on the strength 
of the results of Russian President Boris Yeltsin's visit to 
Tokyo in October last year, towards large-scale development of 
bilateral relations and intensification of the political 
dialogue remains unchanged, he said. 
  The level of mutual understanding reached between the two 
sides during the Russian leader's visit rendered the relations 
between the two countries civilised, taking them out of the 
category of sensations which were unnecessary at times, the 
Russian Foreign Ministry staff member said. "We are prepared to 
continue to maintain such a level of mutual understanding in 
future as well," he added. 
  Upon mentioning that he has available so far only 
preliminary 
and conflicting information on the latest developments in 
Japan's political life, the Russian diplomat did not rule out 
the possibility that Mr Hata will retain the premiership in a 
new government which the country, judging from everything, will 
get next week. 

</TEXT>

