<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Ministry Aide on Georgia Peacemaking Operation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Defense Ministry Aide on Georgia Peacemaking Operation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2406193394 Moscow ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI in Russian 25 Jun 94 p 
1 </F>

<F P=103> PM2406193394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Gennadiy Sobolev: "Russian Peacekeeping Forces </F>
Move Into Zone of Georgian-Abkhaz Conflict"] 
  [Text] And so, the political debates are behind us, and 
tomorrow, 26 June, as announced by Russian Federation Deputy 
Defense Minister Georgiy Kondratyev, the operation to maintain 
peace in the zone of the Georgian-Abkhaz conflict will begin. A 
sketch map [karta-skhema], published today, has been provided 
for by the agreement on a cease-fire and the disengagement of 
forces. The security zone must be devoid of heavy combat 
hardware -- artillery weapons and mortars of a caliber exceeding 
80 mm, as well as tanks and APC's. This hardware will be 
withdrawn into "collection areas" which are under the control of 
UN military observers. It is also planned to pull Georgian 
troops out of the Kodori Gorge and back across Abkhazia's 
borders, as well as to disband and withdraw from Abkhazia armed 
detachments which arrived there from beyond its borders. 
  Aleksandr Arinakhin, chief of the Russian Federation 
Ministry 
of Defense Sector [napravleniye] for the Leadership of 
Peacekeeping Forces, explains: 
  "I have just returned from Abkhazia, where, by decision of 
the Federation Council, the Russian forces' peacemaking 
operation is getting under way. Right now, our subunits are 
being moved out there. We are expecting other Commonwealth 
countries to participate in this operation. I think it will be 
a success: Third time lucky, as they say, and this is the third 
time we will be separating the warring sides.... So the third 
attempt should be successful. A dispute is now going on over 
why Russia does not have an international mandate for the right 
to conduct such operations. But it had no such mandate before, 
during the previous operations, and it would seem that, owing to 
the indecision of the United Nations, we will not get one in the 
near future either. Although nor do we see evidence of any 
ardent wish on the part of the international organizations to 
quell the conflicts on the territory of the former Union.... 
Which is why we have to act on the basis of our laws and 
international treaties. Let me remind you: Both Abkhazia and 
Georgia requested Russia to carry out the peacemaking operation. 
I will add that the experience of past years has shown that 
Russian peacemaking forces operating in conflict zones do not 
under any circumstances use weapons against peaceful 
inhabitants. So it is that our soldiers understand the 
complexity and the specifics of the forthcoming operation, and 
they are prepared for it." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-41474 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov123_a_94027" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-123 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  23 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev Informs Security Council of Abkhaz Mission </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kozyrev Informs Security Council of Abkhaz Mission </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2406132294 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1918 
GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2406132294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Boris Sitnikov] </F>
  [Text] United Nations, 23 Jun -- Russia has officially 
informed the UN Security Council that CIS collective 
peacekeeping forces are being deployed in Abkhazia for a period 
of six months in order to prevent fresh bloodshed in the 
conflict zone. This is stated in a letter from Russian 
Federation Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev to UN 
Secretary-General Butrus Butrus-Ghali which was distributed here 
today as a Security Council document. 
  "The situation in Abkhazia and in the Republic of Georgia 
remains very tense and there is a continuing threat of fresh 
bloodshed. The fact that there are still over 250,000 refugees 
and displaced persons there means that no eventuality can be 
ruled out. This includes the possibility that elements which 
are not under the control of either side could destabilize the 
situation," A. Kozyrev noted. 
  The minister pointed out that although the international 
community realizes that a peace-keeping operation in the Abkhaz 
region "is indispensable," it has been reluctant to adopt a 
decision on forming a UN force for peacekeeping in Abkhazia, on 
the grounds that "conditions are not ripe" yet. "However, as far 
as the peacekeeping operation is concerned, the time factor has 
now become critical if peace is to be secured and the necessary 
conditions created for further progress toward a political 
settlement," A. Kozyrev stressed. 
  He recalled that in the agreement on a cease-fire and 
disengagement of forces, which was signed in Moscow on 14 May, 
the Georgian and Abkhaz sides appealed to the Council of CIS 
Heads of State to adopt a decision on the use of collective 
peacekeeping forces in the zone of the Georgian-Abkhaz conflict. 
Furthermore, the parties sent a special appeal to President 
Boris Yeltsin of Russia, who is chairman of the Council. 
  "Acting on the basis of Chapter XIII of the UN Charter, the 
commonwealth decided to send collective forces to the conflict 
zone for a period of six months. An advance party, consisting 
of Russian forces already stationed in Abkhazia, is being 
deployed right away," the document says. 
  It points out: "The commonwealth is not seeking to take the 
place of UN efforts, but to help create the best possible 
conditions for them to work. Therefore, it is important to 
establish, right from the outset, close cooperation between the 
peace-keeping forces and the UN observer mission in Georgia. We 
hope the Security Council will decide to increase the strength 
of this mission and to expand and clarify its mandate." 
  Russia expressed hope that the establishment under UN 
auspices of a special voluntary fund to finance peacekeeping 
operations in Abkhazia "will help to attract a wide range of 
states to peacekeeping work." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

