<H3> <TI>   Federation Council Addresses Parliaments of CSCE States </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Federation Council Addresses Parliaments of CSCE States </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2406121694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1148 GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2406121694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS parliamentary correspondent Lyudmila Yermakova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 24 TASS -- The Federation Council on 
Friday issued an address to the parliaments of the Conference on 
Security and Cooperation in Europe (CSCE) member-states in 
connection with the passage of a citizenship law by the Latvian 
Sejm. 
  The Sejm passed the law "in defiance of numerous protests by 
the international public and without reckoning with the 
recommendations of the CSCE, the Council of Europe, and a number 
of international experts", the address pointed out. Thereby, 
the Latvian authorities "ignored the universally recognised 
standards in the field of human rights," the Council stated. 
  The Russian parliamentarians, the address said, cannot 
remain 
indifferent to the position of the members of national 
minorities restricted in their right to receive Latvian 
citizenship. In this connection they believe that Latvia's 
further destiny, the ensurance of its genuine, not imaginary, 
national security and the possibility of the creation of a 
democratic law-governed state will in many respects depend on 
the world community's and, first of all, CSCE states' and 
parliaments' stand on the issue, the address pointed out. 
  The Federation Council called on them "to uphold the 
principles of humanism that are being asserted in Europe and to 
prevent Latvia from slipping down to an aggressive nationalism 
and the emergence of a seat of tension in the Baltic region". 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

