<H3> <TI>   Zhirinovskiy To Demand Kozyrev's Resignation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Zhirinovskiy To Demand Kozyrev's Resignation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2306150494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1256 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2306150494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The leader of Russia's Liberal Democratic Party 
Vladimir Zhirinovskiy intends to demand that the Foreign 
Minister Andrey Kozyrev resign for signing the Partnership for 
Peace accord. He said in an exclusive interview with Interfax 
on Thursday that "Kozyrev had no right to sign this program 
since the Duma spoke unequivocally against it." 
  Kozyrev signed the paper at NATO's Headquarters in Brussels, 
thereby making Russia a party to the NATO initiative. 
  Zhirinovskiy threatened to abrogate the treaty since it was 
not legally binding. The signature of one person "when 
parliament spoke against is meaningless", he maintained. 
  He also argued that "no state will take the document 
seriously since the legislature objects to it." Without 
agreement with it, any signing is absurd, Zhirinovskiy declared. 
  He also announced that the LDP [Liberal Democratic Party] 
faction has a nominee to the foreign minister's office. 

</TEXT>

