<H3> <TI>   Amur Organizations Protest Anticrime Edict </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Amur Organizations Protest Anticrime Edict </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2506090994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0720 GMT 25 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2506090994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Khabarovsk June 25 TASS -- A number of 
socio-political movements in Amur area, in a message to the 
president, the Federal Assembly and Government of the Russian 
Federation, have expressed strong disagreement with the methods 
suggested by President Boris Yeltsin to combat crime. 
  They pointed out that the recently signed presidential 
decree 
runs counter not only to the norms of criminal procedure 
legislation but also to major provisions of Russia's 
Constitution. 
  The message is signed by representatives of the Khabarovsk 
regional branch of the Economic Freedom Party, the territorial 
organisation of the Peasant Party, and the "Land and People" 
social foundation. 
  The signatories believe that the presidential decree will 
not 
protect the population against organised crime but would bring 
society back to the times of universal angst, people's 
suspiciousness with regard to one another, and would lead to 
violations of human rights and unfounded repressions. 

</TEXT>

