Daily Report 
<DATE1>  27 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Regional Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Operation To Combat Crime Launched in South </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Operation To Combat Crime Launched in South </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2706082194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0724 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2706082194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Anatoliy Yurkin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 27 TASS -- The poach-control operation 
"Putina-94" inflicted a blow on criminal gangs in Russia's 
south, militia Colonel Aleksandr Skurtul, deputy chief of the 
poach-control operation headquarters, said in an interview with 
ITAR-TASS on Monday. 
  Militia officers seized 149 firearms (including 
submachine-guns) from law-breakers, several thousand rounds of 
ammunition, 45 explosives and considerable quantities of 
grenades. 
  Militia officers exposed over 20 previously committed crimes 
and detained 248 criminals who were on the wanted list. In 
Skurtula's opinion, criminal families in the Caspian region now 
make attempts to restore their operations after suffering 
considerable damage (authorities instituted 305 criminal cases). 
For instance, a carrier of caviar was recently detained on the 
Astrakhan-St. Petersburg train with 487 cans of caviar. 
  According to Skurtula, the poach-control operation is 
expanding. Interior Ministry forces are now joining fight to 
preserve national wealth in the Far Eastern region. Experience 
gained in the Caspian region will help to carry out succesfully 
operational measures. 
  "The underworld quickly responds to our actions. Therefore, 
the struggle will be difficult and long," Skurtul said in 
conclusion. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

