<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Concern at Falling Oil Exports Via Russia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Concern at Falling Oil Exports Via Russia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2406184094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1612 GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2406184094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Kazakh Government has decided to speed up the 
commissioning of an oil pipeline from Atyr oil fields to the 
Chimkent and Pavlodar refineries via Aktyubinsk and Kzyl-Orda 
regions. The measure follows the country's dwindling oil 
exports which almost completely dried up in May, President of 
state Munaigaz holding company (production, refining and 
marketing of fuel) Bulat Yelemanov said in an interview with the 
Kazakh Panorama newspaper. 
  Kazakhstan whose annual oil output runs at about 17 million 
tonnes has no direct access to export pipelines or sea ports 
having to export crude oil via Russian territory. 
  Experts say the project will cost some $500 million to 
implement. Yelemanov said that a 7 km-length pipeline to be 
commissioned by the end of 1996 had already been laid down. 
  He accused Russia of blocking all outlets for Kazakhstan's 
oil exports. Yelemanov said Russian oil agencies offer too high 
prices for pumping oil through Russian territory or refer to 
overcapacity on export pipelines. Worse still, Russian oil 
refineries which handle Kazakh oil now refuse to accept it 
because of glut. 
  Officials in Alma-Ata [Almaty] maintain that Russia does not 
want to honor its obligations. It has now agreed to handle only 
one million tonnes of Kazakhstan's crude oil instead of three 
million tonnes as provided under the contract. Experts say the 
country exported only 285,500 tonnes of crude via Russia in the 
first quarter of this year, which is 75 percent of last year's 
level. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

