<F P=100> Tajikistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tehran Talks Unlikely To Produce Cease-Fire Agreement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tehran Talks Unlikely To Produce Cease-Fire Agreement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2606204794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 2039 GMT 26 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2606204794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [by ITAR-TASS correspondent Oleg Kuzmin] </F>
  [Text] Tehran 26 June TASS -- The second round of talks 
between the Tajik Government and opposition leaders, which is to 
complete here on Monday, has not marked any considerable 
breakthrough so far. According to well-informed sources, the 
conflicting sides are unlikely to sign an agreement on a 
cease-fire for the period of the Tehran talks. However, the 
negotiating parties still hope to break the deadlock. 
  The second round of Tajik talks is expected to result in 
signing a protocol to reiterate the commitment of both the 
former Soviet republic's government and anti-government forces 
to a political settlement of their differences at the 
negotiating table, the U.N. special envoy for Tajikistan told 
TASS on Sunday [26 June]. Another protocol is expected to be 
signed with a view to set up a joint commission, which will 
discuss settlement issues in periods between the rounds of 
talks. This commission will work in Moscow. 
  In their respective interviews with TASS, the negotiating 
parties accused each other of dragging out the talks and 
rejecting any compromises. A Russian observer noted, however, 
that the opposition leaders could give up linking the proposed 
cease-fire to political amnesty in Tajikistan, termination of 
criminal proceedings against political detainees and freedom to 
political parties and the press. The government delegation 
agrees to these demands in principle, but stresses that a 
cease-fire should come first. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

