<F P=100> RUSSIAN NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shakhray: `Most People' Favor Prolonged Presidency </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shakhray: `Most People' Favor Prolonged Presidency </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2506160194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1444 GMT 25 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2506160194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Political equilibrium in the country is such that 
most people would favour prolonged presidential and 
parliamentary powers, Vice-Premier Shakhray, leading the Duma's 
PRES [Party of Russian Unity and Accord] faction, has declared 
in an exclusive interview with Interfax. In his opinion, such 
prolongation could be welcomed even by the opposition "since 
none of its leaders would stand a chance to win the 1996 
presidential race." 
  Shakhray is convinced that such possible extension could be 
objected only by the ex vice-president Aleksandr Rutskoy and 
that part of the political opposition which is not represented 
in the Federal Assembly. He stressed that the key role in 
persuading the public to accept such possibility could be played 
by "regional political elite", which would support it, if the 
powers of all authorities, from top to bottom, were prolonged to 
contribute to stability. 
  He believes that the president would "keep a pause" on the 
matter longer than anyone else. 
  "In a transitional period, elections makes it possible to 
let 
the steam off a politically explosive boiler and thereby prevent 
what happened on October 3-4, 1993," Shakhray believes. 
  As a legal basis to make this idea work, Shakhray suggests 
that a law be passed to introduce amendments into the 
constitution for an interim period. However, he emphasized that 
its passage would require no less than two thirds of votes in 
the Duma and three fourths of votes in the Federation Council, 
and its ratification would need support from two thirds of the 
Federation members. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

