<F P=100> RUSSIAN NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Volskiy: Proposal To Extend Term `Immoral' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Volskiy: Proposal To Extend Term `Immoral' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2406151094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1348 GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2406151094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Russian Businessmen Union's President Arkadiy 
Volskiy has dismissed as immoral Federation Council Chairman 
Vladimir Shumeyko's recent proposal to prolong the mandates of 
the Federal Assembly's deputies. 
  "Each of the deputies went to elections, knowing that he 
would be elected for two years," Volskiy declared at a 
news-conference in Moscow Friday, noting that the prolongation 
offer was "very mean towards the State Duma and Federation 
Council." 
  He also criticized the presidential anti-crime decree since 
it presupposes the right of arbitrary rule. However, he quoted 
a number of industrial managers as saying that most people are 
in favor of the decree. 
  "The best thing would be to erase from the decree the 
rubbish 
like the right to detain people for 30 days," Volskiy said. 
  According to him, "it was in fact Russia rather than the 
USSR 
that collapsed" in 1991. "The rupture of economic ties was the 
chief reason for production decline," he remarked. 
  In his opinion, Russia and other former USSR republics 
should 
set up a really workable economic union, if they want to 
overcome the crisis as soon as possible. Otherwise, enterprises 
will have to establish direct ties, he said. The problem could 
also be resolved by forming transnational corporations across 
the former USSR. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

