<F P=100> RUSSIAN NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shakhray Views Anticrime Edict, Deputies' Mandate </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shakhray Views Anticrime Edict, Deputies' Mandate </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2406183994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1710 GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2406183994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vladimir Khodii] </F>
  [Text] Irkutsk June 24 TASS -- "The presidential decree 
against gangsterism is the first step in extraordinary 
legislation against crime. Attitudes to the decree may differ 
but I think we are doomed to this," Russian Vice-Premier Sergey 
Shakhray told correspondents here today. 
  Shakhray has finished a trip to the extreme northern areas 
with a governmental delegation to analyze goods supplies and 
will attend a meeting of the council of the "Siberian Agreement" 
interregional association. 
  Efforts of all power branches should be pulled in measures 
against organized crime, stressed Shakhray. A corresponding 
draft law has been approved by the government and submitted to 
the State Duma. 
  Asked about his opinion of the proposal to prolong powers of 
deputies, the president and other power structures, Shakhray 
said "i almost do not doubt that the deal of political elites -- 
prolongation of the Civic Accord Treaty -- will not result in 
any elections till the end 1998. This can be legalized only 
with a constitutional amendment or a constitutional law". 
  Speaking of goods delivery to the extreme northern areas, 
Shakhray said extreme measures will have to be taken if the 
goods are not transported on rivers in July. This first of all 
goes for oil products, coal and foodstuffs. Otherwise, they 
will have to evacuate residents from the extreme zones. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

