<F P=100> RUSSIAN NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prosecutor's Office Discusses Organized Crime </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Prosecutor's Office Discusses Organized Crime </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2706082994 Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA in Russian 24 Jun 94 
First Edition p 2 </F>

<F P=103> PM2706082994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Vladimir Klimov: "Working Together"] </F>
  [Text] Yesterday's enlarged sitting of the collegium of 
the Russian Federation General Prosecutor's Office involving 
prosecutors from the republics, krays, and oblasts, and military 
and transport prosecutors, was devoted to the theme of the fight 
against crime. State structure representatives, including 
Presidential Staff Chief S. Filatov, Federation Council 
Committee Chairman I. Kostoyev, and Human Rights Committee 
Chairman S. Kovalev, took part in the collegium's work. 
  The trend toward a rise in organized crime, which is 
destabilizing the atmosphere in society, was noted in the report 
by Acting General Prosecutor A. Ilyushenko, as well as in the 
speeches by regional prosecutors and those by the leaders of law 
enforcement organs. 
  Various appraisals of the president's edict were heard. 
Federal Counterintelligence Service Director S. Stepashin 
declared: "I am in favor of violating the rights of the 
individual if that person is a criminal." S. Kovalev 
categorically disagreed with this conclusion, placing the 
emphasis on the unswerving fulfillment of human rights and 
compliance with the spirit and letter of the Constitution. 
  Other speeches also noted the possible danger of "going too 
far" in terms of human rights compliance when fulfilling the 
president's edict. 
  The collegium called on prosecutors to consider the fight 
against crime and the coordination of the actions of the law 
enforcement bodies the most important area of their activity. 
It was proposed that constant surveillance over compliance with 
legislation be guaranteed when carrying out measures stipulated 
by the president and the parliament to protect the population 
from organized crime. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

