Daily Report 
<DATE1>  27 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIAN NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chernomyrdin Explains Foreign Investment Policy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chernomyrdin Explains Foreign Investment Policy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2706133394 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1016 
GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2706133394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Oleg Velichko and Gennadiy </F>
Yezhov] 
  [Text] Moscow, 27 Jun -- We are wholly in favor of 
channelling most of the finance Russia receives from abroad 
directly into the investment sphere, Viktor Chernomyrdin told 
today's session of the Consultative Council on Foreign 
Investment in the office of the Russian Government. 
  The head of the cabinet expressed confidence that there 
already exists the necessary prerequisites for shifting the 
emphasis of Western financial support for reform in Russia. 
Traditional loans whose repayment is directly guaranteed by the 
Russian Government should be abandoned in favor of targeted 
financing for specific projects, based on collateral and other 
ways of ensuring that loans are repaid, he remarked. 
  Chernomyrdin singled out five main areas on which the 
Russian 
Government will focus as it implements policy on attracting 
large-scale foreign investment. 
  First, it will strive to ensure that legislation regulating 
the activities of foreign investors is as complete and settled 
as it should be. 
  Second, it will seek changes to the tax system designed to 
stimulate production and investment. 
  Third, it will pursue a vigorous investment policy, in the 
context of which it intends to allocate most centralized 
financial resources on a competitive basis, promote mixed (state 
and private sector) funding, provide government guarantees for 
investment and improve the system of insurance for capital 
investment. 
  Fourth, competition in industry and, especially, banking 
should be given the utmost encouragement. 
  Fifth, foreign investors will be given the legal information 
they need. 
  The prime minister referred to legal enactments regulating 
enterprises with foreign investment that are in the pipeline. 
He said that draft laws envisaged a number of major changes to 
the tax position of foreign investors. Enterprises with foreign 
investment are expected to be exempted from profits tax for five 
years after registration. Restrictions on operations connected 
with the movement of capital are likely to be lifted and foreign 
investors (i.e. enterprises with 100 percent foreign capital) 
will be granted the right to own land on which they build new 
enterprises, installations, or production facilities. 
  Furthermore, enterprises with foreign investment will be 
allowed to keep all the hard currency earnings from exports of 
their own goods. Machinery, technological equipment, spare 
parts, raw and other materials, components,and semi-finished 
goods that enterprises import for their own production needs 
will be exempted from tax levies and customs duty. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

