<F P=100> RUSSIAN NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Predicts Billions in Foreign Investment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official Predicts Billions in Foreign Investment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2706102394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1003 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2706102394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Oleg Velichko and Gennadiy </F>
Yezhov] 
  [Text] Moscow June 27 TASS -- The inflow of foreign 
investments in the Russian economy will reach 10-15 billion 
American dollars per annum by the year 2000, according to First 
Deputy Economics Minister of Russia Yakov Urinson. He spoke at 
a meeting of the Consultative Council on Foreign Investments 
under the Russian Government which opened in Moscow's President 
Hotel today. 
  The meeting is being attended by the leaders of 14 major 
transnational corporations of the world. 
  "So far the annual growth rate of foreign investments has 
been recorded at a low level, Yakov Urinson said. This year, 
for example, the total amount of investments reached a mere one 
billion dollars, less than in Estonia. Russia is behind such 
countries as Poland, Hungary and some others as regards foreign 
investments. As of June 1, 1994, only 14,000 enterprises with 
foreign capital has have been recorded on the Russian state 
register. 
  Nonetheless, its attempts to lure cautious Western investors 
Russia scored tangible results in stabilising its economic 
conditions, Urinson said. Economic restructuring is being 
carried out along with demilitarising the Russian economy -- 
over the past two years and a half the military order was cut by 
70 per cent, inflation does not exceed 10 per cent a month over 
the past five months. More than 40 per cent of the Russian 
labour force are employed in private enterprises, and the 
rouble's buying capacity against the dollar has increased by 12 
per cent over the past five months of this year. 
  Enterprises with foreign capital have created approximately 
300,000 new jobs, productivity has increased by 1.5 to two times 
on average as compared to similar domestic enterprises, Urinson 
said. 

</TEXT>

