<F P=100> RUSSIAN NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Nuclear &amp; Military Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Grachev on Defense Ministry Support for Arms Industry </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Grachev on Defense Ministry Support for Arms Industry </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2506115294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1106 GMT 25 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2506115294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Valeriy Rudenko] </F>
  [Text] Tula June 25 TASS -- The Russian Defence Ministry is 
doing all it can for keeping alive unique arms-manufacturing 
enterprises and to ensure their development in the future, 
Russian Defence Minister Pavel Grachev said today at a 
graduation ceremony, held at the Tula Higher Artillery School, 
named after the Tula proletariat. 
  He stressed he wanted the Russian Armed Forces to be 
powerful 
and mobile, fitted with modern weapon systems and capable of 
ensuring Russia's security. According to Grachev, Russia's 
military doctrine does not regard any country as an enemy, but 
Russia has its own vital interests, which a strong and highly 
efficient army should protect. 
  Grachev praised the performance of the artillery school in 
training skilled military personnel. Today graduation diplomas 
were given to another 300 young lieutenants, who will put into 
effect the army reform. 
  The Russian defence minister had a meeting today with senior 
officials of Tula and the Tula region, as well as 
representatives of the regional union of industrialists and 
entrepreneurs, of which directors of arms-manufacturing 
enterprises make the backbone. He visited as well the arms 
museum and attended a ceremony of opening the day of the city. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

