<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Seimas Council Views Baltic Meeting With Clinton </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Seimas Council Views Baltic Meeting With Clinton </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2506150594 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0813 
GMT 25 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2506150594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vladas Burbulis] </F>
  [Text] Vilnius, 25 Jun -- Lithuania's foreign policy 
blueprint, the forthcoming Riga meeting between the heads of the 
Baltic states and the U.S. President on 6 July, the progress of 
the talks with the CIS, and the recently formulated draft law on 
the diplomatic service were discussed in the Seimas on Friday at 
a session of the coordinating council on foreign affairs. Its 
head is Lithuanian President Algirdas Brazauskas. 
  According to a report from the republic's media, 
presidential 
adviser Justas Paleckis told journalists that Lithuania's 
foreign policy blueprint has been drawn up and will shortly be 
submitted for discussion by the members of the Seimas. 
"Lithuania must more actively integrate itself into West 
European economic, political, and military structures, while 
maintaining good relations with all countries in the world, and 
primarily with its neighbors, purposefully play the part of an 
East-West `bridge' and become a country of international 
transit. That is, perhaps, the essence of Lithuania's foreign 
policy blueprint," he stated. 
  It was also noted at the session that, at the meeting with 
the U.S. President, it will be necessary to seek a reinforcement 
of the moral support for independence by economic and social 
measures, by attracting U.S. investment and also through 
cooperation in the economic and scientific domain. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

