Daily Report 
<DATE1>  27 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Central Bank Head: Litas Stability `Must Be Preserved' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Central Bank Head: Litas Stability `Must Be Preserved' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS2706105094 Tallinn BNS in English 1003 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2706105094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Vilnius, Jun 27, BNS -- Lithuania's national 
currency the litas became quite strong during the year that 
passed since its introduction, and such stability must be 
preserved, say the present and previous leaders of the 
Lithuanian central bank. 
  The litas was introduced June 25, 1993 when the central bank 
was headed by Romualdas Visokavicius. He told reporters Friday 
that the introduction of Lithuanian national currency was 
praised by the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank. 
In Visokavicius' view, the Currency Board, which was set up 
after the litas was pegged to the U.S. dollar, will not survive 
long. 
  Meanwhile, the bank's current head, Kazys Ratkevicius, 
maintains that the Currency Board, whose task is to preserve a 
stabile litas- dollar rate, is very useful to the country's 
monetary policy. But both Ratkevicius and Visokavicius noted 
that tying the litas to Western hard currency is not enough for 
the economy to start recovering. Lithuania's industry and gross 
domestic product must be aimed at Western standards, as well, 
Visokavicius said. 
  In Ratkevicius' view, an important factor helping to 
preserve 
a stabile litas are the central bank's receipts in hard 
currency. The chief banker said the bank purchased around 60 
million U.S. dollars over the past three months. 
  Ratkevicius also informed reporters that 500 and 1,000 lit 
bills have already been printed, but there is no need to release 
them into circulation yet. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

