<F P=100> CAUCASUS </F>
<F P=101> Armenia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Iran `Principal Consumer' of Armenian Machinery </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Iran `Principal Consumer' of Armenian Machinery </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2706061994 Yerevan SNARK in English 1236 GMT 26 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2706061994 </F>
<F P=104>  Yerevan SNARK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Business SNARK" file] </F>
  [Text] Yerevan [dateline as received] -- Iranian market has 
become the principal consumer of Armenian machinery. Last year, 
over 90 percent of machine export went to Iran, for a sum 
totalling nearly half-million dollars. As told the head of 
machine-production Administration in the Armenian Industrial 
Ministry, Vardgues Majaryan, appearance at the Iranian market 
has saved many machine- building plants in Armenia from 
bankruptcy, since the CIS market, due to blockade and transport 
problems, has become inaccessible. During the whole last year 
only 70 machines were exported to CIS countries. However, as 
thinks Majaryan, the relatively high demand for Armenian 
machines in Iran is not an escape from the hard situation in 
which the industry has found itself. The thing is that Iranian 
market has purely consumptional and mediatory character, rather 
than industrial purposes. Thus the milling engine, which costs 
4 to 5 thousand dollars, is sold to Iran at a half-price. As 
thinks the head administrator, the production of heavy machines 
in Armenia is not justified, since their sale is difficult. The 
machine building industry passes today to the output of small 
universal machines, the demand for which is rather high. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-41570 </DOCNO>
