<H3> <TI>   Council Seeks Review of Crime Edict </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Council Seeks Review of Crime Edict </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2406192894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1843 GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2406192894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Members of the Russian Federation Council decided to 
appeal to the Constitutional Court with a request to examine the 
anti-crime decree issued by President Boris Yeltsin. 
  A total of 64 deputies (36 percent of the total number) 
voted 
for this decision. In accordance with provision 125 of the 
Constitution, at least one fifth of the Federation Council 
deputies must back an appeal to the Constitutional Court. 
  The appeal was initiated by deputies Aleksandr Belyayev, 
Yuriy Boldyrev and Aleksey Manannikov. 
  Belyayev said in an interview with INTERFAX that the 
Constitutional Court could consider the appeal this autumn after 
the State Duma adopted the law on Constitutional Court at second 
reading. 

</TEXT>

