<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hold Positions on Conflict Line </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hold Positions on Conflict Line </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2406115494 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0727 
GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2406115494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Sergey Ostanin] </F>
  [Text] Sukhumi, 24 Jun -- Subunits of the Russian 
peacekeeping forces today occupied positions on the line of the 
Georgian- Abkhazian confrontation and took checkpoints and 
observation points under guard. The bulk of the peacekeeping 
forces consists of subunits of the airborne troops and the group 
of Russian troops in the Transcaucasus, ITAR-TASS has learned at 
the headquarters of the joint command of the group of the 
peacekeeping forces. 
  The Abkhazia side is represented in the security zone by an 
airborne battalion. The Inguri GES [hydroelectric power 
station], am important strategic point, which is supplying 
electricity to Georgia and Abkhazia, has been placed under 
guard. Following a forced march from Batumi to Zugdidi, 
Georgia's motor rifle battalion has arrived in the region. 
  The HQ of the joint command of the group of the peacekeeping 
forces says that the introduction of troops has been carried out 
after the completion of engineering work. It is thought that by 
29 June subunits of the peacekeeping forces will occupy all 
checkpoints, and that by 9 July engineering work will be 
completed at all posts and deployment sites. 
  It has been reported that the 345th regiment deployed on the 
territory of the Sukhumi military sanatorium will not be taking 
part in the peacekeeping mission. Deputy Defense Minister 
Georgiy Kondratyev told ITAR-TASS that the introduction of the 
peacekeeping forces to Abkhazia is proceeding according to 
schedule. In his words, the entire area is not to be cleared of 
mines. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

