<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Begin Patrolling Safety Zone </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Begin Patrolling Safety Zone </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2406154194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1445 GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2406154194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Sergey Ostanin] </F>
  [Text] Sukhumi June 24 TASS -- Russian peace-making troops 
reached today the Georgian-Abkhazian confrontation line after a 
many-kilometer march and started to protect posts and patrol the 
safety zone along the Inguri river. The zone is 44 kilometers 
long and 24 kilometers wide, head of the press center of the 
peace-making troops in Abkhazia Vitaliy Gerasimov told ITAR-TASS 
today. 
  Routes and helicopter pads have been prepared by an 
engineering unit in accordance with the schedule of 
peace-makers' introduction. Two ammunition storages have been 
revealed on the Gali-Zugdidi line during works in the 
rain-washed ground. One of the storages contained 40 boxes with 
shells, the other -- 600 mines. They are being rendered 
harmless. 
  According to Gerasimov, the troops were located in the area 
without any incidents. The Russian servicemen are staying at 
two check points protecting the bridge to the north of Inguri 
and at 18 control-observer posts. There are five check points 
and ten posts in the south. All in all, there are four mobile 
groups in the safety zone. 
  The main goal of the peace-makers is to clear the zone of 
various weapons, including fire arms and guns, said Gerasimov. 
An area of materiel concentration is being formed in Ochamchira 
and Akhuti. 
  The population took the troops arrival with understanding 
and 
well-wishing feelings. They hope that the six-months-long 
mission of Russian servicemen in Abkhazia will help to restore 
peace in Abkhazia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

