<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nadareishvili Reviews Peacekeeping Operations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nadareishvili Reviews Peacekeeping Operations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2706083994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 0627 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2706083994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Georgian Deputy Prime Minister Tamaz Nadareishvili 
told Interfax Sunday that as the peacekeeping operation was 
getting underway, Georgian guerilla units were being withdrawn 
from the Abkhazian bank of the Inguri River, in particular the 
Kodor canyon and the Gali, Ochamchira and Sukhumi districts. 
  June 26 is the day when the operation officially started in 
the Georgian-Abkhazian war zone. Russian paratrooper and 
motorized infantry units, trained for peacekeeping operations, 
are taking positions on both banks of the Inguri. Mine clearing 
has started and a bridge on the river is being repaired which 
will hopefully enable Georgian refugees to return to their home 
in Abkhazia. 
  Nadareishvili said that nearly 30,000 refugees had returned 
to the Gali District. The local authorities made jobs, bread 
and sugar available to them. Vladislav Ardzinba, chairman of 
the Abkhazian parliament who visited the area three days ago and 
talked to its residents, did not rule out the possibility of 
setting up local government made up of Georgians. 
  Nadareishvili admitted that the return of refugees to the 
Gali District would probably take 12 to 18 months. 
  He said that Georgian could hardly be able to maintain its 
territorial integrity as long as the Abkhazians dictate their 
own terms. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

