<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Conference Discusses Ukrainian Issues, NATO Plans </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Conference Discusses Ukrainian Issues, NATO Plans </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2406211994 Kiev UNIAR in Ukrainian 1410 GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2406211994 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UNIAR </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kiev, 24 Jun -- The international conference 
"Partnership for Peace: objectives and prospects," organized by 
the National Institute of Strategic Research of Ukraine, is 
under way. John Barrett, chairman of NATO's Political Affairs 
Division, Ukrainian Deputy Foreign Minister Borys Tarasyuk, and 
Vadym Hrechaninov, assistant to the defense minister for issues 
of military policy, took part in the conference among others. 
  The conference participants discussed NATO's attitude toward 
the "Partnership for Peace" program and analyzed the state's 
military planning and armament policy in connection with the 
"Partnership for Peace" initiative. The issue of 
Ukrainian-Russian relations within NATO's "Partnership for 
Peace" initiative did not remain beyond the attention of the 
conference participants. 
  Today, the conference participants discussed prospects for 
Ukraine's defense policy and the Ukrainian issue within NATO's 
plans. NATO's representative John Barrett delivered a report on 
the geopolitical location of Ukraine and its influence on NATO's 
plans for the implementation of the "Partnership for Peace" 
program. The participants in the conference analyzed the 
political, economic, and military aspects of this issue. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

