<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kuchma Appeals for Support in South Ukraine </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kuchma Appeals for Support in South Ukraine </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2406165194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1619 GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2406165194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Galina Nekrasova] </F>
  [Text] Lvov 24 June TASS - On the eve of the forthcoming 
presidential elections in Ukraine, which are scheduled to be 
held on 26 June, presidential candidate Leonid Kuchma has 
appealed for support from residents of the south Ukraine, so as 
to relieve him of accusations of taking a "pro-Moscow" stand. 
  He explains to electorates that Ukraine cannot survive 
without close ccoperation with Russia. "One can hate the Russian 
autocracy, Stalinstic terrorism, but what it has got to do with 
contemporary economic cooperation with Russia," Leonid Kuchma 
said. "I am against dictatorship of Moscow, but for equal and 
mutually beneficial relations," he said. 
  It is difficult to say, how far effective this appeal will 
be. West Ukrainian electorates sympathize with current president 
Leonid Kravchuk. Three years ago at the first presidential 
elections they had opposed Kravchuk, and had supported his only 
adversary Vyacheslav Chernovil. Now there mood has taken a 180 
degree turn. 
  Undoubtedly, West Ukrainian votes won't be decisive in 
Sunday's presidential elections, but they can have a significant 
effect on the fate of one or the other candidate. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-41622 </DOCNO>
