<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kuchma Criticizes U.S. for Not Delivering Promised Aid </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kuchma Criticizes U.S. for Not Delivering Promised Aid </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2606172594 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
1600 GMT 26 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2606172594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Vesti" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Speaking at polling station No. 4 in Kiev, Leonid 
Kuchma today told Western correspondents that 90 percent of the 
Ukrainian people are on the brink of poverty. Everyone abroad 
seems to think that everything is nice and quiet in Ukraine. 
However, the danger of transforming Ukraine into a new 
Yugoslavia persists. Kuchma was obliquely criticizing the 
United States, which had promised economic aid to Ukraine in 
exchange for its nuclear disarmament. For now, all we have 
received are words, but not a cent. 
  Kuchma believes that there is no problem with the Crimea. 
The conflict there is a myth used for political purposes, he 
said. These words are regarded as a hint on Kravchuk's position. 
The former Ukrainian prime minister also said that no one can 
order the Russians to leave Sevastopol. 

</TEXT>

