<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk Promises Help for Crimea's Drought-Stricken Areas </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kravchuk Promises Help for Crimea's Drought-Stricken Areas </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2406183694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1708 GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2406183694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS special correspondent Viktor Demidenko] </F>
  [Text] Dzhankoi (the Republic of Crimea) 24 June TASS -- 
Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk does not regard his tours of 
the country as a campaign for once again being elected to the 
country's top most post. He considers them as visits by the 
head of state, who wants to acquaint himself with the state of 
affairs in Ukraine, he said this after his arrival in the 
republic of Crimea due to the unprecedented drought that has 
struck the peninsula's steppe areas. According to old residents, 
they have not seen such a dry summer during past 20 years. 
  President Kravchuk was received at the Dzhankoi airport by 
Crimean Supreme Soviet Chairman Sergey Tsekov and other 
officials. But President of the Crimean Republic Yuriy Meshkov 
was not seen among them. During a press conference on the 
tarmac, Leonid Kravchuk said he does not regard this as a big 
tragedy. 
  The Ukrainian president told journalists that he intends to 
personally acquaint himself with the situation prevailing in the 
area due to the drought, and decide what help is needed by the 
people and farms. 
  When asked about his chances of once again being elected 
president, Leonid Kravchuk replied that every person has his 
chances, but they are determined by the electorate, who come to 
cast their votes. 
  Regarding the Black Sea Fleet problem, Leonid Kravchuk said 
that his stand remains unchanged. According to him, statements 
made by certain political leaders about not dividing the fleet 
and decide bases, do not stand up to criticism. "The fact is 
that this view pint is not shared by Russia and, in particular, 
by President Boris Yeltsin." "Besides this, the president 
emphasised, there is a law adopted by Ukraine's Supreme Soviet, 
which states that the fleet be divided and bases for ships must 
be determined. And I, as head of state, must carry out this," 
he said. 
  Speaking of basing ships, Leonid Kravchuk emphasised that 
the 
Black Sea Fleet base should not be designated as the city of 
Sevastopol, but as Russia's Black Sea base in Sevastopol. 
According to him the Ukrainian Navy, apparently, will be based 
in Balaklav. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

