<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk Says New Constitution To Solve Crimean Problem </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kravchuk Says New Constitution To Solve Crimean Problem </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2406192094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1612 GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2406192094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk told journalists 
Friday that the differences between the Constitutions of Ukraine 
and Crimea could be resolved by adopting a new Ukrainian 
Constitution, which would recognize the interests of every 
region and take into account what he called new circumstances. 
Meanwhile, he said, every individual and region had to abide by 
the existing Constitution. 
  Kravchuk thought that as much power as possible could be 
given to Crimea on the proviso that Ukraine remained an integral 
whole. 
  He recalled that under Ukrainian legislation and 
international law Crimea was part of Ukraine and this should not 
be changed. 
  The conflict of Crimean and Ukrainian legislation started on 
20 May 1994 when the Crimean Supreme Soviet restored the initial 
6 May 1992 wording of the Crimean Constitution under which the 
relations between Crimea and Ukraine were to be guided by a 
treaty between them and Crimean residents could have dual 
citizenship. 
  Kiev demanded that the Crimean Constitution be aligned with 
Ukrainian legislation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

