<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk on Relations With Russia, Chernobyl Problem </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kravchuk on Relations With Russia, Chernobyl Problem </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2606114294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1128 GMT 26 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2606114294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondents Viktor Demidenko, </F>
Mikhail Melnik] 
  [Text] Kiev, 26 June (TASS) -- The development of relations 
with Russia should have a priority importance, Leonid Kravchuk 
said today after he cast his ballot at one of the Kiev polling 
stations. "They just cannot be other than a priority for us," he 
stressed. 
  Kravchuk expressed confidence that "no matter who will 
become 
president of Ukraine, he will have to proceed from the 
assumption that relations with Russia should have a special 
status, taking into consideration the past and the future of our 
two countries. If we forget about it, we shall put in a 
difficult situation both Ukraine and Russia." 
  "I shall be very glad if my words are met with understanding 
by the Russian leaders. If we learn to speak about each other 
in this way, to respect each other, I am sure 70 per cent of 
problems we are facing today will be removed. This is the most 
important, the central problem of our policy," he said. 
  "The problem of the Chernobyl power plant is extremely 
important not only for Ukraine, but also for the whole world. 
This is why we welcome the decision of the summit session of 
the council of the European Union to allocate 500 million ECU 
on the implementation of plans of a complete shutdown of the 
power plant, but the sum should be calculated once again," 
Kravchuk said, commenting on the decision of the EU council. 
  The Ukrainian leader told ITAR-TASS that "the first problem 
to be resolved is that of the future of the city, of the people 
who live there... We still do not know how much money is needed 
for resolving the problem of the Chernobyl nuclear power plant." 

</TEXT>

