<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk Terms Slav Union Idea `Dangerous' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kravchuk Terms Slav Union Idea `Dangerous' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2606130094 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1203 
GMT 26 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2606130094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondents Viktor Demodenko, </F>
Mikhail Melnik] 
  [Text] Kiev, 26 Jun -- "Alliances based on ethnic identity 
are dangerous per se, for they inevitably engender nationalism, 
panslavism, and all that ensues from it," Ukraine's President 
Leonid Kravchuk told ITAR-TASS today, when asked about a 
possibility of creating a Slav union. "Both politicians and 
historians condemn it, knowing that that is where aggravated 
nationalism is rooted," he said. 
  Leonid Kravchuk also believes that this question is not 
quite 
specific in practical terms. "As for a union, one should then 
speak in terms of East Slavs, rather than Slavs. Otherwise, 
what should one do with Poland, Slovakia, Yugoslavia, or 
Bulgaria? Thus, the Slavs will be divided into Western Slavs 
and Eastern Slavs," he summed up. One should bear in mind that 
about 30 million Russians, Ukrainians, and Belarusians live 
beyond the borders of Russia, Ukraine, and Belarus. "The Slav 
Union will inevitably create problems for them." "By having such 
a union, we will split in two those states where Slavs and 
non-Slavs live." Kravchuk is convinced that "by this step we 
will begin dividing states of the former Soviet Union." He 
expressed the belief that this would be followed by creating 
Asian and other unions, and "then horrible confrontation will 
begin." 
  "One should not raise questions that are ready to be 
resolved 
today, neither theoretically nor practically. One should live 
and follow the chosen path: build independent states but not on 
the basis of ethnic identity," he said. "We are building a civil 
society in Ukraine and Russia is building the same society in 
its country. If we pursue a different policy a social explosion 
is possible. Russia is also not 100 percent a Slav state." 
  "I advocate economic relations, integration, and the use of 
the CIS in resolving issues that can be resolved by good will," 
Kravchuk said. In his opinion, one should not try and establish 
new structures and organizations immediately, he said. One 
should do everything to avoid confrontation between states and 
peoples, he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-41632 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov123_f_94017" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-123 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  26 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk: Supreme Council Cannot Limit President's Powers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kravchuk: Supreme Council Cannot Limit President's Powers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2606140594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1344 GMT 26 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2606140594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondents Viktor Demidenko and </F>
Mikhail Melnik] 
  [Text] Kiev 26 June TASS -- "Ukraine's Supreme Soviet 
cannot limit the head of state's powers after presidential 
elections" unless the latter agrees to it, Ukrainian President 
Leonid Kravchuk told TASS on Sunday [26 June]. 
  "In case the parliament takes this path, it should first ask 
for the people's approval," he added. 
  If in three months the parliament "raises a question about a 
referendum, this may spell the termination of its activities, 
since people will not stand any new elections or referendums," 
the president believes. 
  Kravchuk is confident that lawmakers will not choose to take 
this move. In his opinion, if the parliament tries to restrict 
the president's powers without his agreement, this will lead to 
confrontation entailing grave consequences. 
  However, Kravchuk fears that left-wing lawmakers may revise 
the course approved by the 1991 people's vote and currently 
pursued by Ukraine. "This may cause confrontation," he said. 
  The president is strongly convinced the people advocates its 
state's independence and such values as personal freedom, family 
and confidence in the future. If a person is not economically 
free to choose the form of ownership, or areas for applying his 
or her intellectual and professional potentials, any talk about 
rights and liberties will be out of place. For these reasons, 
the president believes one should not trifle with such things as 
politics, property, social security and armed forces. 
  We should proceed along the road we have chosen, Kravchuk 
said. We should improve our political line and adjust it, if 
appropriate, that is to revise our tactics rather than strategy. 
Otherwise, we will face confrontation and war, the president 
emphasised in conclusion. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

