<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk Supports Private Ownership of Land </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kravchuk Supports Private Ownership of Land </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2506180094 Kiev UNIAN in Ukrainian 1610 GMT 25 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2506180094 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UNIAN </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Poltava-Cherkassy, [no date as received] -- On 25 
June President Leonid Kravchuk visited Poltava and Cherkassy 
Oblasts, where he met local residents. 
  Replying to a UNIAN correspondent's question on where the 
danger was in the Ukrainian Supreme Council's draft law "on 
introducing amendments and additions to the Ukrainian law `on 
the formation of the bodies of local power and 
self-government,'" which he recently vetoed, and whether he 
assessed this draft law as a deliberate move by the left-wing 
majority in parliament, Leonid Kravchuk pointed out: "This 
draft law was adopted in violation of three articles of 
Ukraine's Constitution, and it does not matter to me who 
violates it, either the left-wingers or the right-wingers, 
because everyone must respect the Constitution, while the 
Supreme Council and the president should provide an example of 
respect. If this kind of attitude toward the Constitution is 
displayed at this level, then it is necessary to announce that 
we have no Constitution and that we live in compliance with 
current laws which are adopted either by the left-wing or the 
right-wing majority." 
  As far as private ownership of land is concerned, which 
Supreme Council Chairman Oleksandr Moroz recently spoke out 
against, Leonid Kravchuk replied that neither the president nor 
the chairman of the Ukrainian Supreme Council solves this issue, 
but the Supreme Council of Ukraine does, as a legislative body, 
proceeding from the proposals to be put forward by the regions, 
as well as the decisions by the oblast councils and also 
people's will. "I have already said that all the talk about 
democracy, citizens' rights, and freedoms should be discontinued 
if a citizen of Ukraine, who wants and who can buy a plot of 
land is banned from doing this," said Leonid Kravchuk. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-41636 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov123_f_94021" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-123 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  27 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

