<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Secret Service To Cooperate With Russians </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Secret Service To Cooperate With Russians </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2406182394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1642 GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2406182394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Valeriy Demidetskiy] </F>
  [Text] Kishinev [Chisinau] 24 June TASS -- Russian and 
Moldovan secret services should pool their efforts against 
criminal activities that threaten the safety of Russian and 
Moldovan citizens, Moldovan National Security Minister Vasile 
Calmoi said here today before signing the treaty on cooperation 
with the Russian Federal Counter-Intelligence Service. 
  Service head Sergey Stepashin arrived in Kishinev today on 
an 
official visit. 
  The treaty provides for information exchange and interaction 
of the Russian and Moldovan secret services against terrorism, 
contraband, illicit arms sales, drug trafficking. The two 
services will also prevent attempts of citizens of third states 
to use Russian and Moldovan territories for illegal transit. 
  The sides take an obligation not to carry out force or 
subversive actions against each other. In the words of Calmoi, 
Moldova and Russia have signed similar agreements with the 
Ukrainian Secret Service. 
  The treaty is another proof that Russian secret services 
plan 
no subversive actions against Kishinev, a representative of the 
Russian Federal Counter-Intelligence Service's delegation told 
ITAR-TASS. Russia keeps to unconditional recognition of 
independence and territorial integrity of Moldova. 
  Speaking of the Trans-Dniester problem, the official said it 
"should be settled only peacefully and the Federal 
Counter-Intelligence Service will help it with all legal means." 
  Stepashin and Calmoi will leave for the Trans-Dniester 
region 
on Saturday to visit Russian troops stationed in the area. 

</TEXT>

