Daily Report 
<DATE1>  24 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIAN NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shumeyko on Extending Powers of President, Parliament </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shumeyko on Extending Powers of President, Parliament </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2406193194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1811 GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2406193194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] No official statements proposing to extend the 
powers of the Federal Assembly and the president have as yet 
been received, Federation Council Speaker Vladimir Shumeyko told 
Interfax today. 
  Speaking of the negative reaction to the proposal to extend 
the powers of the president and deputies, Shumeyko said from 
what he had read in yesterday's newspapers it was clear that 
those who wanted no stability were making the sharpest 
statements and distorting the situation. 
  Shumeyko said his statement did not mention the president, 
while PRAVDA maintained that he had done all this for the 
president. He said he concluded from response of Sergey 
Baburin, Mikhail Gorbachev, SOVETSAKAYA ROSSIYA and PRAVDA that 
he was not backed by those who did not want stability. He said 
this was proof that his statement had hit the mark. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

