<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   ITAR-TASS Carries Press Review for 25 Jun </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    ITAR-TASS Carries Press Review for 25 Jun </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2506064094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0512 GMT 25 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2506064094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Press Review" -- ITAR-TASS headline] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 25 TASS ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI carries a 
report about the concluding of Viktor Chernomyrdin's visit to 
the U.S. Under the headline "Al Gore Enthusiastic, Chernomyrdin 
Reserved." The Russian prime minister attended in the U.S. a 
regular session of the intergovernmental Russian-American 
commission on economic and technological cooperation. U.S. Vice 
President Albert Gore described the results of that work as 
remarkable success. 
  TRUD publishes in this connection an interview with 
Chernomyrdin, who assures the public that the money spent on the 
visit did not go to waste, including from the social point of 
view. "What are actually the contracts on space exploration that 
the delegation is bringing home?" the journalist asked 
Chernomyrdin. The prime minister said in reply that "in fact, 
they mean support for our industry, specifically, its branches 
connected with arms manufacturing, those where conversion is now 
going on, which are in a difficult situation today." He pointed 
out that Russian-American relations were assessed only in a 
positive way and rejected inventions of those 'prophets' by both 
sides of the Atlantic, who predict the worsening of those 
relations. "This is out of the question. Our relations are 
improving and will continue to improve," Chernomyrdin said. 
  The newspaper carries contradictory comments of deputies to 
the State Duma about the recent decree of President Yeltsin "On 
urgent measures to protect the population from gangsterism and 
other manifestations of organised crime." For example, A. 
Ledzins from the December 12 group believes that if the decree 
is put into effect, this will get Russia back by more than 50 
years, to the period when the dividing line between law and 
arbitrariness actually ceased to exist. However, N. Travkin, 
leader of the Democratic Party of Russia, thinks that it is too 
late already to try and resolve the crime problem with the help 
of civilised methods. "Instead of arguing with the decree, it is 
necessary to adopt as quick as possible the laws that will 
permit to really start tackling it," he said. 
  KRASNAYA ZVEZDA and other newspapers highlight President 
Yeltsin's statement at the Kerkira island, Greece, who said that 
the agreement on partnership and cooperation between the Russian 
Federation and the European Union, signed there, is a document 
of great historic importance, which made it possible to take a 
decisive step towards the restoration of unity in the european 
continent. In the opinion of KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA, one of major 
results of Yeltsin's trip is that the European Union and Russia 
will start looking for ways to create a free trade zone. 
  KRASNAYA ZVEZDA publishes an interview with Aleksandr 
Tushinskiy, first deputy defence minister of Belarus, who is 
advocating the restoration of ties between the two countries, 
including between Russian and Belarusian arms-manufacturing 
enterprises. 
  NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA highlights the results of presidential 
elections in Belarus, where, according to the preliminary 
results, the lead was captured by Aleksandr Lukashenko, head of 
the parliamentary anti-mafia commission, who got 40-45 per cent 
of votes. In this connection the newspaper describes as 
"political amateurishness" appeals in the State Duma, 
specifically those of Konstantin Zatulin, chairman of its 
committee for ties with CIS member states, who urged at a 
special press conference to support Belarusian Prime Minister 
Vyacheslav Kebich at the elections in Belarus, and ex-prime 
minister Leonid Kuchma -- at the elections in Ukraine. In the 
opinion of the newspaper, Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk is 
"the only politician who is capable of keeping Ukraine away from 
sliding down from economic difficulties to political 
confrontation of individual regions and social groups." 
  SOVETSKAYA ROSSIYA writes that, by voting for Lukashenko, 
"Belarusians actually voted against Yeltsin," because the 
Russian president had a meeting with Kebich shortly before the 
elections. The newspaper describes Kebich's visit to Moscow as a 
"gross mistake". In its opinion, the trip eroded his prestige, 
because Yeltsin in not popular in Belarus. 
  Ths same idea is expressed by PRAVDA in its article on this 
subject, which is entitled "Lukashenko Packing Suitcases of his 
Rivals." The newspaper highlights the words of Yuriy Belov, 
chairman of the central executive committee of the Communist 
Party of the Russian Federation, who believes that "socialism 
has not disappeared, because the communist movement in Russia 
has not disappeared either." In his opinion, opponents of 
socialism "are especially afraid of its new image", which is in 
line with historic traditions of the great Russian nation. 
  NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA carries an article about prospects of 
settling the Russian-Chechen crisis. It writes that the 
relations between the two countries (on the level of 
authorities) "have entered a new stage of development." 
President Yeltsin's decision to start talks with the Chechen 
authorities, the recent trip of Chechen President Dzhokhar 
Dudaev to Sochi and the "pro-Yeltsin tone of official statements 
coming now from Groznyy" are proof to that, the newspaper points 
out. However, the initial stands of the two sides are 
diametrially opposed to each other, and this is why the talks 
are not going to be easy. 

</TEXT>

