<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   NATO Commander Starts Visit to Russia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NATO Commander Starts Visit to Russia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2706120594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1036 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2706120594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The working visit of General George Joulwan, 
commander- in-chief of NATO forces in Europe, to Russia began on 
Monday. 
  Officials in the Russian Defense Ministry's press and 
information service told Interfax that Joulwan would meet with 
National Security Council secretary Oleg Lobov, First Deputy 
Minister Oleg Soskovets, Colonel General Mikhail Kolesnikov, 
chief of the General Staff, and MPs on June 27. 
  Joulwan's meeting with Army General Pavel Grachev, the 
Russian Defense Minister, and a joint news conference with him 
are scheduled for Tuesday. 
  Other plans for his stay in Russia include a meeting with 
ambassadors of NATO member nations in Moscow and a visit to the 
27th Separate Motorized Brigade stationed in Teplyy Stan, a 
southern neighborhood of Moscow. 
  Observers believe that the Joulwan visit reflects closer 
ties 
between Russia and NATO. Russian diplomats told Interfax that 
the Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev had signed a 
protocol on working out a Russia-NATO cooperation program 
simultaneously with the Partnership for Peace framework program. 
The two sides are said in the protocol to have agreed to 
continue broad Russian-NATO cooperation both inside and outside 
the Partnership for Peace program. 
  Russia and NATO also agreed to continue a dialog on both 
political and security problems in Europe, political 
consultations and cooperation on security. 
  Russian diplomats pointed out that the very fact of signing 
the protocol implied the existence of special relations between 
the North Atlantic Alliance and Russia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

