<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Holds Talks With Soskovets </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Holds Talks With Soskovets </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2706150594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1355 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2706150594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Oleg Velichko] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 27 TASS -- First Vice-Premier of the 
Russian Government Oleg Soskovets and commander-in-chief of 
NATO's joint armed forces in Europe, George Joulwan, currently 
on a visit to Russia in the framework of cooperation between 
Russia and NATO, came out for the expansion of cooperation 
between Russia and the North Atlantic alliance. 
  During their meeting today, the first Russian vice-premier 
said the "world community pins its hopes on Russia, the United 
States and NATO for the maintenance of world peace." Soskovets 
pointed out that the participation of Russian peace-keeping 
forces in Yugoslavia and Georgia shows that "Russia is making 
considerable efforts for promoting peace." Besides, Russia is 
responsible for the protection of borders in Tajikistan, 
prevention of conflicts in the Caucasus and keeping the 
situation on Moldova under control, Soskovets added. 
  He drew attention to the fact that Russia, in fact, has been 
carrying out complex and unilateral conversion practically 
without any assistance by foreign partners. He pointed out that 
"the policy of conversion would be continued in accordance with 
Russia's military doctrine." 
  For his part, the NATO commander said that after the sides 
had signed the partnership for peace programme, possibilities 
opened for developing closer contacts. Joulwan said that the 
Partnership for Peace is "a road with two-way traffic." It is 
not only Russia that can learn something from NATO, but NATO can 
take over much of Russia's experience, Joulwan said. "The time 
has come to work out concrete documents determining the degree 
of Russia's participation in NATO's programmes," the NATO 
official said. 

</TEXT>

