<H3> <TI>   Further on Soskovets Meeting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on Soskovets Meeting </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2706152994 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 1400 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2706152994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Novosti" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The fact that NATO's Partnership for Peace program 
has already become part of Russian policy was confirmed today at 
a meeting between Oleg Soskovets and George Joulwan, NATO's 
commander in chief in Europe. In a conversation with the U.S. 
general, the first deputy prime minister noted that the CIS 
countries have not become really independent since gaining 
political independence. In the Caucasus, Tajikistan, and 
Moldova, Russia is forced to conduct peacekeeping missions. 
Moreover, it hopes for assistance in these operations from the 
North Atlantic alliance. 
  The NATO commander in chief agreed with the first deputy 
prime minister's assessment of the situation in CIS trouble 
spots, and stressed that NATO is undergoing a period of 
transformation from a military bloc into a peacekeeping one. 
However, it is in no haste to participate in such operations. 
George Joulwan proposed to Oleg Soskovets that joint 
Russian-NATO exercises be held in any European country of 
Russia's choice and at a time convenient to it. Russia agrees 
in principle. The details will evidently be discussed tomorrow 
at George Joulwan's meeting with [Defense Minister] Pavel 
Grachev. 

</TEXT>

