<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Meets Yushenkov, Discusses Relations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2706151594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1404 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2706151594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Sergey Ostanin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 27 TASS -- Russia's signing of the 
Partnership for Peace programme and the protocol on cooperation 
with NATO opens up wide possibilities for the development of 
military and technical ties, a Russian top legislator said on 
Monday. 
  The announcement was made by Sergey Yushenkov, chairman of 
the State Duma Committee for Defence, during his meeting with 
Supreme Allied Commander Europe George Joulwan who is in Moscow 
on a working visit. 
  Yushenkov and Joulwan discussed relations between NATO and 
Russia and European security. 
  Earlier today, Joulwan met with Russian Chief of the Army 
General Staff Mikhail Kolesnikov to discuss prospects for 
cooperation between the Russian army general staff and the NATO 
Supreme Command Europe, interaction in peace-keeping operations 
and other issues of mutual concern, the Russian Defence Ministry 
press centre said. 

</TEXT>

