<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Discusses Balkans With Kozyrev </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Discusses Balkans With Kozyrev </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2706165994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1610 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2706165994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Those members of the State Duma who on June 22 said 
in parliament that Russia's joining NATO's Partnership for Peace 
betrays national interests are traitors themselves, the Russian 
Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev said today. He was speaking 
before his meeting in Moscow with the Commander-in-Chief of 
NATO's allied forces in Europe George Joulwan. 
  "They are political red-brown bastards who want to plunge 
Russia into isolation again. They need an enemy", Kozyrev said. 
  He said that Russia would in any case take a decent place in 
the world and would most probably hold a joint military exercise 
with the United States. "We've got nothing to be afraid of. On 
the contrary, a refusal would be tantamount to sticking one's 
head in the sand", he said 
  About the conflict in the Balkans Kozyrev said that uneasy 
calm had been established there and that it was still fraught 
with a slide into World War III. 
  He said that the "parties of war" in the Balkans were trying 
to win support from the great powers and as a matter of fact 
provoking a collision between them. 
  Kozyrev said that Russia was for addressing both sides with 
a 
firm demand to observe peace without giving preferences to 
either of them. 
  "Those traitors in the Duma who demand supporting one of the 
parties thereby push us into a war with the United States. 
"Apparently they would like to fish in troubled waters, just as 
was the case in 1917, and Mr Ziuganov seeks to outdo his 
predecessor". 

</TEXT>

