<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deputy Foreign Minister Views Partnership for Peace </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Deputy Foreign Minister Views Partnership for Peace </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2706155894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1529 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2706155894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature: Correspondents Igor </F>
Porshnev, S Kolosova and others] 
  [Text] "Whenever something serious and positive happens in 
Russia's foreign policy, it invariably causes somebody's 
criticism,, the Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Aleksandr Panov 
has told IF. He was speaking in reply to the opposition 
leaders' strong criticism of Russia's joining the NATO 
"Partnership for Peace" program. 
  The Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev signed the 
program in Brussels last Wednesday. The "Russia-NATO" protocol 
was adopted on the same day. "This is a serious, important 
step" Panov said. 
  He believes that criticism expressed over the past few days 
was counterproductive, because it contained no alternative or 
any other proposals. "They (the opposition - IF) simply don't 
like it. Probably, this is inevitable when political struggle is 
afoot. But criticism must be well-founded. Otherwise it is 
just not serious at all," Panov said. 

</TEXT>

