<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Views Prospects for Conference on Korea </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry Views Prospects for Conference on Korea </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2806104794 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0855 
GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2806104794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Andrey Kirillov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 28 Jun -- Assessing the prospects for the 
Russian Government's proposal to hold an international 
conference on security on the Korean peninsula and nuclear-free 
status for it, Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Aleksandr Panov 
said that "if the current bilateral contacts between the United 
States and North Korea fail, there will be no alternative." 
  In an interview with ITAR-TASS, he described the chances for 
this Russian initiative as "very strong." The diplomat believes 
that if the bilateral dialogue between the United States and the 
DPRK fails, it will become clear that "our position is 
absolutely right," since it is based on common sense. 
  Aleksandr Panov considers that the consultations between the 
United States and the DPRK, between North and South Korea, and 
between the DPRK and the International Atomic Energy Agency 
[IAEA] could be rolled into one. "Our proposed format is the 
best way of going about this," he noted. 
  Russia, he said, now believes that the number of 
participants 
in the conference on Korea could be increased. He said that, in 
addition to the DPRK and the Republic of Korea, it could be 
attended by the United States, Japan, Russia, China, and 
representatives of the United Nations and the IAEA, as well as 
Britain and France. France has already expressed a wish to take 
part. "We have always said that our proposal is not something 
sacrosanct," the Russian diplomat said, adding that each party 
is free to express its feelings and additional suggestions as 
regards the conference idea. 
  The situation on the Korean peninsula deteriorated after the 
DPRK announced it was leaving the IAEA and that it might also 
withdraw from the Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

