<H3> <TI>   Churkin Says UN Forces May Leave Bosnia-Herzegovina </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Churkin Says UN Forces May Leave Bosnia-Herzegovina </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2706163194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1530 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2706163194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature: By correspondents </F>
Igor Porshnev, S. Kolosova, and others] 
  [Text] Russia's Foreign Ministry does not rule out that the 
date for a second ministerial meeting on a settlement in Bosnia 
can be agreed at a Contact Group's session in Paris on Tuesday 
[28 June]. As a senior Russian diplomat reported to Interfax on 
Monday, Russia will be represented at the gathering by the 
Deputy Foreign Minister Vitaliy Churkin. 
  He confirmed that the second ministerial conference would 
most likely take place in Geneva, where the first gathering had 
been held. "It is to put an end to three years of drama in 
former Yugoslavia, a drama that has exasperated everyone in the 
world community", Churkin remarked. 
  In his words, the Contact Group will look at alternative 
world community responses to refusal by one or both belligerents 
to a plan for territorial division in Bosnia, endorsed at the 
previous Geneva meeting, and it is not ruled out that UN may 
leave former Yugoslavia," Churkin said. 
  In keeping with the plan, the Serbs who now control 70 
percent of Bosnia, are to get 49, and the Moslems and Crates [as 
received] - 51 percent of the territory. 

</TEXT>

