<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Greek Minister on Moscow's `Stabilization' Role in Balkans </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Greek Minister on Moscow's `Stabilization' Role in Balkans </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2706175194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1736 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2706175194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Yuriy Malinov] </F>
  [Text] Athens June 27 -- The Greek Defence Minister 
Yerasimos Arsenis said in an interview carried by the TA NEA 
newspaper on Monday that Russia, taking part in NATO's 
Partnership for Peace programme, might play an important 
stabilising role in the Balkans. He pointed out that 
preparations for signing an agreement on cooperation between 
Greece and Russia in the military sphere are under way. 
  The Greek defence minister said that he was given an 
opportunity to talk with the Russian President Boris Yeltsin and 
the Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev before their 
departure from Athens. During the meeting the sides confirmed 
that the Greek defence minister would visit Moscow next month. 
Aresnis said that during the visit, like during his recent trip 
to the United States, the sides will discuss problems of 
security in the Balkan region and the eastern part of the 
Mediterranean region. 
  Speaking about the system of collective security in the 
region, the Greek defence minister said that the Partnership for 
Peace programme envisages interaction between NATO and former 
Comicon countries. In this framework, Greece might put forward 
initiatives, urging for certain kinds of cooperation with other 
neighbouring countries at a political and military level, and 
possibly, with such nato countries as the United States. 
  The U.S. Defence Minister William Perry is arriving in 
Greece 
on an official visit on July 19. The sides will discuss 
problems of cooperation between the two countries with the aim 
of creating a system of security in the region, the Greek 
defence minister said. According to Arsenis, Greece, as a member 
of the European Union and NATO, might assume a certain decisive 
role in the Balkans on behalf of these organsations. 

</TEXT>

