<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Duma Defense Chief Views Russia's Arms Trade Goals </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Duma Defense Chief Views Russia's Arms Trade Goals </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2706182594 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1131 
GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2706182594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondents Dmitriy Gorokhov and </F>
Andrey Shitov] 
  [Text] Moscow, 27 Jun -- "Russia should carry on arms trade 
on the same principles on which states in the West engage in 
this trade," ITAR-TASS reported today, quoting Sergey Yushenkov, 
chairman of the State Duma's defense committee. 
  Yushenkov described various laws currently in the pipeline 
and said that as a result of Western competition, the United 
States' share of some 30 percent of world arms trade market in 
1987 had now climbed up to almost 60 percent in 1993, as against 
Russia's five percent. 
  Yushenkov also said that Russia had already concluded 
contracts to deliver planes to Malaysia worth approximately 600 
million dollars this year and that Thailand was interested in 
Russian arms and the Russia's Scud system in particular, said to 
be much more effective that the Patriot system. Russia was also 
trying to enter the Latin American markets, ITAR-TASS said. 
  Yushenkov praised the Partnership for Peace deal signed by 
Russia recently and recalled that "Western Europe has still not 
extended the most favored nation status to Russia in full. The 
bans, especially those affecting quantity, affected the output 
of military industrial enterprises." 
  Sergey Yushenkov hoped that having now joined the 
Partnership 
for Peace program Russia would now regain, if only partially, 
its previous stature on its traditional Polish, Czech, and 
Slovak markets, where there was a need for spare parts for 
Russian arms purchased at an earlier stage, ITAR-TASS concluded. 

</TEXT>

