<H3> <TI>   Paper Refuses To Reveal Sources on Foreign Guns Deal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Paper Refuses To Reveal Sources on Foreign Guns Deal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2406152994 Moscow NOVAYA YEZHEDNEVNAYA GAZETA in Russian 
24 Jun 94 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> PM2406152994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NOVAYA YEZHEDNEVNAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Letter from V. Kvasov, Russian Federation minister and </F>
leader of the Government Apparatus, dated 20 June 1994, followed 
by reply from NYG Managing Editor Dmitriy Muratov under the 
"State Secrets" rubric: "We Report, Mr. Kvasov: This Is 1994!"] 
  [Text] For official use 
  To S.N. Kozheurov, chief [glavnyy] editor of NOVAYA 
YEZHEDNEVNAYA GAZETA 
  Dear Sergey Nikolayevich! 
  On 16 June this year your newspaper carried a report 
divulging the contents of Russian Federation Government 
directives stamped "Not for the Press" on the purchase from the 
FRG and Austria of special property for the needs of the Russian 
MVD [Ministry of Internal Affairs] and FCS [Federal 
Counterintelligence Service]. 
  I ask you to conduct an investigation and to report to the 
Russian Federation Government Apparatus on the source of the 
aforesaid information and the grounds on which it was printed. 
  [Signed] V. Kvasov, minister of the Russian Federation and 
leader of the Russian Federation Government Apparatus. 
  Dear Mr. Minister! 
  In a letter sent by courier you demand an indication of the 
grounds on which the information about the government's purchase 
of a large quantity of foreign weapons (Walthers, Colts, 
Winchesters, Parabellums, etc.) and ammunition for them was 
published. 
  I report: The grounds are that this is interesting 
information. 
  You ask for its source to be reported. 
  I reply: in accordance with the Law on the Press... only in 
court. 
  If you deem it possible to shift onto us the responsibility 
for the regime of secrecy in the Government Apparatus, I will 
point out that it is not journalists who must keep your terrible 
secrets but you yourselves. 
  We really do not understand very well why Tula or Vladimir 
"products" are not purchased for the FCS and the MVD and the 
government is evidently more attracted to deals outside Russia's 
"Golden Ring." Incidentally, as our newspaper reported 21 June, 
Boris Nikolayevich personally bought himself a rifle in Tula for 
14 million rubles. 
  A final point. The Government Apparatus has not reacted so 
harshly to NOVAYA YEZHEDNEVNAYA GAZETA's articles about lobbyist 
edicts on the part of Chernomyrdin and Yeltsin in respect of a 
number of firms. But in general this makes me feel better: If 
there are state secrets, could this mean that the state exists? 
  [Signed] [NOVAYA YEZHEDNEVNAYA GAZETA Managing (vedushchiy) 
Editor] Dmitriy Muratov. 

</TEXT>

