<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rybkin Favors More Fiscal `Leeway' for Regions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rybkin Favors More Fiscal `Leeway' for Regions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2706163394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1443 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2706163394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ivan Rybkin, State Duma chairman, told journalists 
in Petropavlovsk-Kamchatsky that the country's regions had to be 
given more leeway and that the Duma would do just that in 
discussing the 1995 budget. He thought that the Russian Far 
East could solve its problems without federal subsidies. 
  Rybkin currently heads a group of parliamentarians touring 
Siberia and the Far East. 
  Asked about the proposal, made by Vladimir Shumeyko, 
chairman 
of the Federation Council, the upper house of the Russian 
parliament, that elections to the the Federal Assembly be put 
off, Rybkin emphasized that parliament had to earn this honor 
and that two-thirds of the country's regions and republics had 
to endorse this step. 
  He admitted that people were obviously tired of elections 
but 
said that the logic of life as well as the Constitution were 
against this step. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-41709 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov124_d_94008" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-124 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  28 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rybkin Stresses Russian Rights to Kuril Islands </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rybkin Stresses Russian Rights to Kuril Islands </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2806091694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0818 GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2806091694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Pavel Kuznetsov] </F>
  [Text] Yuzhno-Sakhalinsk June 28 TASS -- Russian State Duma 
speaker Ivan Rybkin said the disputed Kuril Islands claimed by 
Japan should remain Russia and be granted special rights in 
economic development. 
  "The Kurils are our Russian islands", Rybkin said on Tuesday 
after visiting the picturesque Iturup Island. He quoted local 
residents as telling him that "such beauty should not be lost". 
  Rybkin stressed that it is necessary to pay more attention 
to 
the development of the islands "especially in the current crisis 
conditions in economy". He proposed to adopt a law on the 
Kurils and Sakhalin which will "grant special rights to the 
region mostly in economic issues". This would be for the 
benefit of Russia in general, according to him. 
  The speaker also urged to pay more attention to the military 
serving on the islands. He said the unit which he visited on 
Iturup has only 21 per cent of the necessary personnel and faces 
constant financial problems. "It is necessary to decide once and 
for all that the units deployed on the islands should be manned 
first and have priority in getting all the necessary supplies", 
Rybkin said. 
  He welcomed the recent anti-poaching operation held near the 
Kuril Islands as it ended the ambiguity to who the islands 
belong. "This was not just a training for coast guards, but 
protection of our economic interests", he said and added that "a 
certain ambiguity regarding the Kuril Islands gives rise to a 
desire of some countries to go and make a profit at the expense 
of others (by fishing) actually in our internal waters". 
  Rybkin stressed that such actions are completely 
inadmissible 
in other countries. 

</TEXT>

