<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Vladivostok Ship Repair Plant in Financial Straits </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Vladivostok Ship Repair Plant in Financial Straits </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2706150594 Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA in Russian 24 Jun 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> PM2706150594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Leonid Burovets from the "Fax News" roundup in </F>
the "Russkoye Oruzhiye" section: "That's All. We Would Seem To 
Have Run Aground"] 
  [Text] Vladivostok -- The two and a half years of life 
under a so-called market economy have been sheer torment and 
torture for our ship repair plant. In the first five months of 
this year alone, the Pacific Fleet has run up debts to the plant 
in the order of 13 billion rubles [R]. This, in turn, includes 
R525 million in administrative fines and penalties which the 
plant owes to the state budget, the pension fund, and 
enterprises keeping us going on a day-to-day basis. Workers 
have not received their pay for three months running, and any 
attempt to explain to people why this is happening immediately 
turns into a spontaneous rally. Today, the plant's debts come 
to R2.5 billion. 
  Another few days of operation, and then we will grind to a 
halt. We have run aground. The main directorate is asking that 
production continue even at the cost of halting military ship 
repairs altogether and occupying production capacities with any 
output. But how long will these measures last? 

</TEXT>

