<F P=100> Tajikistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tehran Communique Urges Cease-Fire; Next Talks in Islamabad </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tehran Communique Urges Cease-Fire; Next Talks in Islamabad </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2806101394 Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network in Persian 0930 GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2806101394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network </F>

<F P=105>  Persian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] The second round of Tajikistan peace talks, which 
began in Tehran 10 days ago, ended this morning and the two 
sides reached some agreements on ways to implement a cease-fire. 
  During this round of talks, held in our country's Foreign 
Ministry Institute for Political and International Studies since 
last Saturday under the auspices of the UN secretary general's 
envoy, the two sides signed a joint communique today, stressing 
the need to abandon hostility and accept national 
reconciliation. Although the communique has not specified a 
timetable for implementing the agreements reached, the two sides 
have stressed the importance of implementing the cease-fire, 
halting illegal detention, and stopping any offensive operations 
and troop movements in Tajikistan and along its borders. 
  Also in this communique, the representatives of the 
Tajikistan government and the opposition groups have reached 
some agreements on the next round of talks in Islamabad and 
discussion on the issues related to the mechanism of controlling 
the cease-fire. The agenda of the second round of Tajikistan 
peace talks includes four main axes of establishing a 
cease-fire, a general amnesty, return of the refugees, and 
holding elections. The two sides, however, agreed to 
concentrate the main talks on the cease-fire control mechanism. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

