<F P=100> Uzbekistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Comments on Visit to Turkey </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President Comments on Visit to Turkey </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2706170294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1500 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2706170294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" feature; compiled by </F>
Nikolay Zherebtsov, Andrey Petrovskiy; edited by Vladimir 
Shishlin] 
  [Text] Turkey occupies a special place among all countries 
with which Uzbekistan has good relations. This was stated by 
President Islam Karimov after his visit to Ankara. 
  He said that lately certain political forces have been 
dissatisfied with such a state of affairs. He added that 
everything promoting the country's growth and its international 
influence provokes their negative reaction. Karimov said these 
forces shadow relations with Turkey. 
  He said one of the main purposes of his visit to Turkey last 
week was to prove that Uzbekistan and Turkey are interested in 
each other. "I see Turkey as the closest, most reliable 
partner," the president stressed. 
  During the visit Karimov held talks with his counterpart 
Suleyman Demirel. The two sides signed a treaty on legal 
assistance in criminal, trade and civil cases and a protocol 
between the two foreign ministries on cooperation and mutual 
consultations. 
  Karimov urged Turkish businessmen to expand cooperation with 
partners in Uzbekistan and continue setting up joint ventures. 
(There are over 100 such mixed companies in Uzbekistan at the 
moment -- INTERFAX.) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

