<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Trade Deficit Declines in May </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Trade Deficit Declines in May </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS2806092894 Tallinn BNS in English 1507 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2806092894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tallinn, June 27, BNS -- According to customs 
statistics, Estonia exported 1,496.9 million kroons worth of 
goods and commodities in May, while its imports for the same 
month amounted to 1,750.7 million kroons. 
  Imports in May exceeded exports by 253.7 million kroons. 
Estonia's foreign trade deficit declined by 179.1 million kroons 
when compared with April. 
  Exports went up by 202.9 million kroons, and imports by 23.9 
million kroons in one month from April. 
  The country received 11.9 million kroons worth of 
humanitarian aid in May, which accounted for 0.7 percent of the 
imports. The respective figure for April was 21.4 million 
kroons, or 1.2 percent of the imports. 
  Temporary exports under the condition of obligatory 
re-import 
made up 1.8 percent of the country's total exports in May. Re- 
export made up 25.3 percent of the total. Temporary imports 
made up 18.3 percent of the total imports, and re-imports, 0.8 
percent. 
  The country traded in May with partners in 81 nations and 
brought in a positive balance with 44 of them. 
  Estonia's major trade partners and their share of total 
turnover in May were as follows (figures for April given in 
parentheses): 


----------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|                  |percent of total  |                  |percent of total  | 
|                  |export            |                  |import            | 
----------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|Russia            |25.0 (21.0)       |Finland           |39.6 (35.9)       | 
----------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|Finland           |20.0 (21.8)       |Russia            |12.9 (16.9)       | 
----------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|Sweden            |11.8 (13.2)       |Sweden            |10.2 (8.9)        | 
----------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|Latvia            |7.0 (7.6)         |Germany           |9.2 (8.6)         | 
----------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|Germany           |6.5 (5.5)         |Netherlands       |3.2 (3.3)         | 
----------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|Lithuania         |4.1 (6.6)         |Lithuania         |2.6 (2.5)         | 
----------------------------------------------------------------------------- 


  The biggest one-month increase was reported in exports to 
Russia, by 102.5 million kroons, and in imports from Finland, by 
73.5 million kroons. Export to Lithuania went down by 24.1 
million kroons. Imports from Russia decreased by 66.8 million 
kroons, from Denmark, by 19 million kroons, and from Lithuania, 
by 13 million kroons. 
  The major groups of goods exported and imported in May were 
as follows (the figures for April are in parentheses): 


------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|                                      |percent of export                     | 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|agricultural produce                  |22.1 (19.0)                           | 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|timber, wood products                 |12.0 (11.8)                           | 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|non-precious metals                   |9.2 (10.9)                            | 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|clothes                               |8.9 (8.4)                             | 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|vehicles                              |7.8 (7.9)                             | 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|                                      |percent of import                     | 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|agricultural produce                  |15.3 (15.9)                           | 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|equipment                             |10.4 (10.1)                           | 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|electrical machines                   |10.1 (7.8)                            | 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|vehicles                              |9.7 (10.8)                            | 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|mineral fuel, oil                     |8.9 (11.9)                            | 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 


  The customs statistics cover the goods that are declared on 
the border. They don't include data on the export and import of 
foreign cash, electricity and gas. 

</TEXT>

