<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   President To Announce Stand 28 Jun </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President To Announce Stand 28 Jun </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS2706143894 Tallinn BNS in English 1210 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2706143894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Riga, Jun 27, BNS -- Latvian President Guntis 
Ulmanis plans to declare at 1400 on Tuesday at a press briefing 
if he will announce or not the citizenship law, and say about 
his stand in changing of customs tariffs, President's Office 
told BNS. 
  During his meeting with Aluksne inhabitants on Saturday, 
Ulmanis admitted that the citizenship law could be sent for 
repeated parliament consideration. 
  "I will ask the parliament to consider the citizenship law 
one more time so that the interests of the Latvian people as 
well as international norms were observed in it," said Ulmanis. 
  As reported, the Cabinet called the president not to 
announce 
the citizenship law, adopted on June 21, but send it for 
repeated parliament consideration. The law's article No. 14 
provides for the quota principle that allows to naturalize each 
year a number of citizens equal to 0.1 percent of the body of 
citizens, starting with the year 2000. 
  The naturalization quota principle endangers Latvia's 
enrollment in the Council of Europe [CE] and the very 
negotiations on the granting the CE associate member status to 
the Baltic country, and that poses a threat to Latvia's further 
integration into the European Union, according to the government 
statement. The quota principle also complicates Latvia's 
entrance into European collective security structures, the 
statement read. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-41730 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov124_u_94003" </HT>


