<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Homeland Union Delivers Letter to President on Selling Land </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Homeland Union Delivers Letter to President on Selling Land </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS2806095494 Vilnius ELTA in English 1911 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2806095494 </F>
<F P=104>  Vilnius ELTA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From "News Bulletin" No. 530 ] </F>
  [Text] Vilnius, June 27, ELTA -- Seimas faction of 
Homeland's Union delivered a letter to Lithuanian President 
Algirdas Brazauskas with the request for Brazauskas to appeal 
to the Constitutional Court to prevent the resolution of the 
government on selling private land. 
  The government made the resolution on selling private land 
in March, and Homeland's Union refused to agree with 
it. 
  According to the resolution, the boards of the districts 
were commissioned until August 1 to register permissions to buy 
2-3 hectare lots for those who would submit requests until July 
1. 
  Monitor of Homeland's Union Andrius Kubilius told a 
news conference that this resolution violated the Constitution. 
"The resolution denies the rights to the property of the former 
landowners", Kubilius maintained. 
  He also reminded that the state could not sell out 2-3 
hectare lots because it was not the owner of the land. The 
state had not bought the land from the owners. The law to 
allot 2-3 hectare lots for a certain category of people was 
passed by the Lithuanian Supreme Council in 1990. However, 
leaders of the opposition claimed that most of the lots were 
alloted illegally. 

</TEXT>

