<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shakhray: `Police State' Possible Response To Crime </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shakhray: `Police State' Possible Response To Crime </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2706162994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1443 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2706162994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russia could become a "police state, and a very 
strong one" in response to growing crime rates, the settling of 
scores in politics and the absence of civilized civic 
institutions, Sergey Shakhray told Interfax. He said that the 
presidential anti-crime decree was one of the first signs of 
emergency legislation on the issue. 
  Shakhray believes that Russia is doomed to live through a 
period of extraordinary legislation. He says that in the 
struggle against banditry and organized crime there can be no 
place for competition between the State Duma, the president and 
other institutions of power. "They still have to pool their 
efforts," Shakhray said. 
  He said that a number of provisions in President Boris 
Yeltsin's decrees had been followed up upon in a draft law 
approved by the government and submitted to parliament for 
approval. The future law would "dramatically enhance 
responsibility for both committing and organizing crimes." 
  "The basic human right is the right to life and the safety 
of 
children and the family. All other rights must be made 
subordinate to that right," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

