<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Filatov Views Necessity of Anticrime Decree </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Filatov Views Necessity of Anticrime Decree </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2706172294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1624 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2706172294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [by ITAR-TASS correspondent Tamara Zamyatina] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 27 TASS -- "During the discussion of the 
president's decree on the protection of the population from 
organised crime and the drive against bandits it became clear 
that the majority of society regards the decree as the necessary 
measure to curb crime in Russia," said Presidential Chief of 
Staff Sergey Filatov, commenting on the president's decree which 
took effect on Monday. 
  As for the opinion of a commissioner for human rights, 
Sergey 
Kovalev, who suggested that the president should recall his 
decree, Filatov said that "his position, strengthened by his 
experience as a human rights advocator, deserves respect." 
  Nevertheless, Filatov said "we believe that we shall manage 
to avoid abuse as regards the rights of an individual when 
applying the president's anti-crime decree." Filatov's opinion 
is shared by the general prosecutor's office which shall 
exercise control over its implementation. "Any incident when a 
suspect is detained should be registered in a protocol and its 
legitimacy is subject to control. An investigation is already 
under way into 17 incidents of detention without sufficient 
grounds, which is also a guarantee of the protection of the 
rights of an individual. Besides, the decree applies only to 
the most violent crimes," Filatov said. 
  "We do not live in totalitarian society. Such a powerful 
weapon as the freedom of speech will be a counterbalance to any 
encroachments on citizens' rights," Filatov said. 
  Filatov pointed out that his worst apprehensions were caused 
by the blending of the criminal world and the world of 
officials. "This "knot" might become a means of settling scores 
with "unwanted" people, which cannot be allowed. The decree on 
the fight against bandits puts a barrier to this dangerous 
process," Filatov said in conclusion. 

</TEXT>

