<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Assures Foreign Investors of Stability </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Assures Foreign Investors of Stability </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2806090994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0744 GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2806090994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Lyudmila Aleksandrova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 28 TASS -- Russian President Boris 
Yeltsin dispelled fears of major foreign corporations about high 
risks of investing into Russia and predicted that stability will 
last in the country at least until the next presidential 
elections in 1996. 
  Yeltsin told a meeting with major foreign investors on 
Tuesday that their fear to work in Russia is "outdated". "The 
recent months were the most quiet in political sense during the 
whole period of reforms in Russia", the president said and 
expressed conviction that stability will continue to dominate. 
  Only before the presidential elections in 1996 "a certain 
political fuss" can occur, he added. 
  The president underlined that the wave of strikes has gone 
down in Russia of late. "Which of your countries has no strikes 
at present? There is no such country, only Russia", he said. 
  Yeltsin welcomed the arrival of major Western businessmen to 
Moscow to participate in the work of the Council on Foreign 
Investments. 
  "You can see for yourselves what the situation in Russia 
is", 
the president said. 
  The meeting was attended by Prime Minister Viktor 
Chernomyrdin and heads of such major companies as ABB, BASF, 
Citicorp, Coca-Cola, Ernst and Young and others. 

</TEXT>

