<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chernomyrdin on Measures To Encourage Foreign Investment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chernomyrdin on Measures To Encourage Foreign Investment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2706160894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1513 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2706160894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Igor Velichko and Gennadiy </F>
Yezhov] 
  [Text] Moscow June 27 TASS -- "We are all for directing the 
main financial streams flowing from abroad into Russia right 
into the investment sphere", Russian Prime Minister Viktor 
Chernomyrdin announced on Monday, speaking at a meeting of the 
Russian Government Consultative Council for Foreign Investments, 
which he chairs. 
  Chernomyrdin commented on upcoming legislation which 
regulates the functioning of and privileges for businesses with 
foreign investment. 
  According to the premier, the draft laws include a series of 
major changes in the tax code for foreign investors. It is 
proposed to free enterprises with foreign capital from the 
profit tax for five years after registration, to remove the 
limitations on capital movement, and to give foreign investors 
(meaning businesses 100 per cent funded by foreign capital) the 
right to own land if they construct a new building or expand 
production. 
  In addition, businesses with foreign capital will be able to 
keep all the profit in foreign currency which they receive by 
exporting goods they produce in Russia. The import of machines, 
technological equipment, spare parts, raw materials, and 
component parts for production uses will not be subject to taxes 
or customs duties. 

</TEXT>

