<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Soskovets: Russia Needs Increased Foreign Investment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Soskovets: Russia Needs Increased Foreign Investment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2706172594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1612 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2706172594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Since the very beginning of the reforms Russia has 
regarded foreign aid as crucial. As a result of this incorrect 
orientation internal sources were not used to stimulate economic 
and investment activities, Russian First Vice Premier Oleg 
Soskovets said at the constituent meeting of a consultative 
council on foreign investments under the Russian government 
today. 
  He said the total volume of foreign investment in Russia 
remained very small and did not conform with the capacities and 
needs of the country. "According to expert evaluations, only 
about 0.1 percent of foreign investments in the world is being 
placed into Russia," Soskovets said. 
  The Russian government realizes that during the next five 
years the economic reforms in Russia will make Russian small and 
medium enterprises the main source of new jobs, Soskovets said. 
  However, Soskovets said there was quite a number of negative 
tendencies in the development of small business. Today there 
are only about 700 enterprises performing in the sphere of small 
business and there should be at least 2.5 million or 3.5 million 
of them. 
  Soskovets said that small business in Russia was not 
receiving enough support on the part of Western capital. He 
added that only the $300 million-credit given to Russia by the 
European Bank was the most significant one allotted by the West 
to Russian small and medium business. Soskovets said he hoped 
that the problems concerning the attraction of Western capital 
to Russia would be settled by the consultative council on 
foreign investments headed by Premier Viktor Chernomyrdin. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

