<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Economics Official Gives Figures on Foreign Investment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Economics Official Gives Figures on Foreign Investment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2706170694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1613 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2706170694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Foreign investments in enterprises on Russian soil 
at the end of 1993 amounted to $2.7 billion and 4.8 billion 
rubles (this includes ruble investments in joint ventures with 
CIS member nations and reinvested rubles). Yakov Urinson, first 
deputy economics minister, told a meeting, held in Moscow 
Monday, of the advisory council on investment policy which 
reports to the government that direct investments (which enable 
the investors to share in the management and made up more than 
10 percent of the enterprise equity capital) accounted for 85 
percent of the total, or for $2.3 billion and 4.3 billion 
rubles. Portfolio investments (which accounted for less than 10 
percent of the equity capital and do not enable the investors to 
share in the management) accounted for as little as 3 percent of 
the entire amount, 70 million dollars. Other kinds of investment 
such as trading credits and financial leasing were equal to $282 
million and 437 million rubles. 
  According to the Russian Economics Ministry, the largest 
share of foreign investments, 23 percent, was made in the 
engineering industry and metal working, followed by the fuel 
industry, 15 percent, trade and catering, 14 percent, 
construction, 6 percent and timber and pulp and cellulose 
industries, 5 percent. 
  The ministry reported that foreign investments increased by 
$1.36 billion and 4.1 billion rubles in 1993. 

</TEXT>

