<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dubinin Says Hyperinflation `Overcome' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Dubinin Says Hyperinflation `Overcome' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2706170994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1543 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2706170994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Russian government will stick to a strict 
financial policy in 1995, though the country has overcome 
hyperinflation, acting Finance Minister Sergey Dubinin told a 
meeting of the government consultative council for foreign 
investments Monday. 
  According to Dubinin, the monthly inflation rate will fall 
from 8-10 percent to 2.5-3 percent at the end of 1995. 
Production growth, if any, will take place no earlier than the 
end of next year. 
  Dubinin informed the meeting of proposals to ease the tax 
climate being prepared. He said some taxes, including VAT 
(currently at 20 percent), would be reduced, and the entire list 
of taxes to be levied in 1995 would be reviewed. 
  The finance ministry is considering emission of stocks which 
could be used for payment of taxes, Dubinin said. He added that 
the government would use a number of tax privileges in order to 
attract foreign investments to the top-priority industries. 

</TEXT>

