<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Nuclear Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spokesman Denies CW Information Concealed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Spokesman Denies CW Information Concealed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2806123494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1111 GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2806123494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Claims that Russia is concealing information about 
chemical weapons are "totally groundless". Such a statement was 
made in an interview with INTERFAX on Tuesday by the Foreign 
Ministry's Spokesman Grigoriy Karasin following accusations made 
in the course of congressional hearings in the U.S. recently. 
  He reported that in keeping with an intergovernmental 
memorandum on chemical agents, Russia and U.S. had exchanged 
data on their military and chemical potentials in May. 
  "This data is being studied and analyzed in Russia and the 
U.S. after which, in accordance with the memorandum, each 
country will carry out five inspections of the other country's 
facilities. This will enable them to make sure that the data is 
correct," Karasin said. 
  He said Russian experts note that the information received 
from the American side needs to be clarified. 
  "We believe that the proper channels of interaction should 
be 
used if these doubts are to be removed." 

</TEXT>

