<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Expert Considers Initial Election Results </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russian Expert Considers Initial Election Results </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2706161094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1449 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2706161094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature: by correspondents </F>
Igor Porshnev, S. Kolosova and others] 
  [Text] The preliminary results of the presidential 
elections in Ukraine revealed diametrically opposed tendencies 
in the east and west of the country, which can ultimately lead 
to a split, a high-ranking Russian expert specializing in 
Russian-Ukrainian relations told INTERFAX on Monday [27 June]. 
He noted, though, that he expressed the opinion of a political 
scientist rather than a diplomat. 
  What happened was easy to predict, he went on to say. The 
west voted for Leonid Kravchuk, who scored 90 percent of the 
votes in Lvov, for instance. The east, including Donbass, 
Zaporozhye and Crimea, voted for Prime Minister Leonid Kuchma, 
who is leading with an impressive preponderance. 
  Obviously, the electors voted for the ideas expressed by the 
candidates, not for the candidates as such. Kravchuk symbolizes 
independence and gradual departure from Russia, while Kuchma -- 
independence and rapprochement with Russia, he said. 
  He also noted that before the Soviet Union's breakup, 
Ukraine 
had never existed as an independent state. The west of Ukraine 
was initially part of Austro-Hungary and then Hungary and 
Poland, while the east had always gravitated to Russia. "The 
conventional border ran along the Dnieper. Hence, the left-bank 
(eastern) and right-bank (western) Ukraine," said the Russian 
expert. The preliminary results of the elections show that the 
historical division was still strongly influencing the alignment 
of political forces in Ukraine, he said. 
  He said he did not want to make far-reaching conclusions. 
"One should not forget, however, that during the 1991 
referendum, 90 percent of the Ukrainian residents voted for 
independence. The situation has changed since then. This is 
the only thing one can say with confidence," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

