<H3> <TI>   Says Voters Lack Confidence in Government </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Says Voters Lack Confidence in Government </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2706120094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1036 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2706120094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Aleksandr Lukashenko, the front-runner in the first 
round of the presidential elections in Belarus, believes that 
his victory is tantamount to a vote of no-confidence in the 
Cabinet. He told a press conference in Minsk that this could be 
judged from the wide gap between the 45.1 percent of the votes 
he garnered, and the 17.4 percent, going to Prime Minister 
Vyacheslav Kebich. 
  He stated, however, that he would not oust all of the 
current 
Cabinet members from their posts, if he were elected president. 
  According to unofficial sources, Lukashenko will offer the 
post of prime minister to the current Vice Premier and Economics 
Minister Sergey Ling. 
  In an exclusive interview with Interfax, Lukashenko's proxy, 
Chairman of the Parliamentary Commission for Legislation Dmitriy 
Bulakhov expressed doubt about the authenticity of the results 
of the first round. However, he refused to comment on the 
rumors about instances of ballot rigging. 
  According to these rumors, in the first round Lukashenko 
actually garnered 56 percent, rather than 45.1 percent of the 
votes, which would have meant his complete victory. 
  Bulakhov expressed hope that Lukashenko would become 
president in the second round. "So, there is no need to cast 
doubts on the official reports of the Central Electoral 
Commission," he said. 

</TEXT>

