<H3> <TI>   Pledges To Remove Top Officials </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Pledges To Remove Top Officials </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2706121994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1141 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2706121994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by BELINFORM correspondent Aleksandr Lyushkevich for </F>
TASS] 
  [Text] Minsk 27 June TASS -- According to Belarusian 
presidential candidate Aleksandr Lukashenko, "all the generals 
and all the leaders of state bodies of power will be removed 
within 24 hours" if he becomes president. 
  However, Lukashenko called rumors that he wanted to kick out 
the whole state apparatus if he is elected groundless. "85 per 
cent of government employees and law enforcement personnel -- 
the police, the KGB, the Interior Ministry, the procurator's 
office -- are respectable and honest people," he announced at a 
press conference in Minsk on Monday. 
  With the exception of the top military and civilian brass, 
Lukashenko and his team are "ready to work and cooperate" with 
government employees. That statement also concerns the 
republic's industrial managers, whose enterprises will be given 
up to January 1, 1995 to "function normally." If they are not 
capable of meeting that deadline, "the heads will be fired," 
Lukashenko explained. 
  The Belarusian candidate refused to exclude the possibility 
that he would invite one of the members of the current 
government to fill the prime minister's seat, if he is elected. 

</TEXT>

