<DATE1>  28 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dniester Parliament Chief Opposes 14th Army Pullout </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Dniester Parliament Chief Opposes 14th Army Pullout </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2806100394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0925 GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2806100394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Valeriy Demidetskiy] </F>
  [Text] Kishinev [Chisinau] 28 June TASS -- The 14th Russian 
Army could be a guarantor against an outside aggression against 
either the Dniester Republic or Moldavia as a whole, Dniester 
parliament chief Grigoriy Marakutsa told ITAR-TASS. 
  Marakutsa favours the conclusion of an appropriate agreement 
with Russia that would specify the status of her troops in the 
region. "This may be a military base of Russia or of a 
peacekeeping force of the CIS," said the leader of parliament of 
the republic unrecognised by Moldavia. 
  A Russian Army came to the region in the days of Empress 
Catherine the Second, and ever since has been the guarantor of 
peace and stability, Marakutsa said. An overwhelming majority 
of the population of left-bank Moldavia agree with this. They 
know quite well who "dampened hot-heads and stopped bloodshed in 
the Dniester area in the summer of 1992," he said. 
  "The 14th Army is not an expeditionary corps temporarily 
deployed on foreign territory," Marakutsa emphasised. "The Army 
officers are rooted in this land. Their houses, families and 
relatives are here." His opinion is that those who press for 
the earliest withdrawal of the Army from the Dniester area know 
well that one can take away only its combat banner and a smaller 
part of hardware but that people would not go. 
  Speaking about the role of Russia in a settlement of the 
Dniester problem, Marakutsa pointed out that hardly any other 
state could play a more positive role than Russia. "Not every 
country would agree to expose its soldiers to danger to help a 
stranger in misfortune. The role of Russia in this respect is 
great and it will grow stronger," the Dniester parliament 
speaker stressed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

