<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dniester Spokesman Favors Cooperation With Russia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Dniester Spokesman Favors Cooperation With Russia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2806102894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0930 GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2806102894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Valeriy Demidetskiy] </F>
  [Text] Kishinev [Chisinau] 28 June TASS -- The Dniester 
Republic favours the development of close economic cooperation 
with Russia, the Republic's parliament chief Grigoriy Marakutsa 
told ITAR-TASS. 
  At the same time he is of the opinion that the relations 
with 
Russia, with which markets of commodities, raw materials and 
technology are linked, are being restrained by the Dniester 
area's uncertain status. For example, Marakutsa said, "we agree 
to independently repay debts to Russia for gas but the Russian 
Gazprom signed an appropriate agreement only with the Moldavian 
[Moldovan] Government." 
  In connection with the fact that the Dniester Republic, 
which 
has not been recognised by Moldavia, cannot pay with its own 
products and money for gas supplied by Russia, Marakutsa 
suggests taking the road followed by Baltic states, Ukraine and 
Byelorussia [Belarus]. His opinion is that one can pay for the 
supplied raw materials and energy resources by property, the 
establishment of joint ventures and apply other economic forms 
of cooperation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

