<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Peacekeepers Enter Abkhazia `Without Incidents' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Peacekeepers Enter Abkhazia `Without Incidents' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2806122294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1112 GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2806122294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] According to the Chief of the Russian Peace-Keeping 
Forces Headquarters, General Kozlov, the introduction of 
peace-keepers into Abhazia has been completed virtually "without 
incidents." 
  A Moscow-based Abkhazi spokesman told INTERFAX that 2500 
Russian peacekeepers have taken up positions on both sides of 
the border between Abkhazia and Georgia. A total of 1400 
paratroopers strong battalions are deployed in a 12-kilometer 
security zone. Two motorized infantry battalions from Adzharia 
are on the other side of the frontier. 
  Engineers from the Russian peace-keeping force in the area 
of 
the Georgian-Abkhaz conflict began to reconstruct the road 
bridge over the Inguri river in the evening of June 27. The 
river forms the dividing line between the two opposing sides. 
The press center of the peace-keeping force told INTERFAX that 
the bridge will be completely rebuilt within a week. 
Peace-keeping troops took control of the Inguri Power Station, 
the largest in Georgia. 
  Starting Monday a curfew has been announced in the security 
zone around the Inguri river from 22:00 to 6:00. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

