<H3> <TI>   61 Percent of District Voters Against Nuclear Station </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    61 Percent of District Voters Against Nuclear Station </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2706170394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1612 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2706170394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A total of 61 percent of voters of the Ukrainian 
Zaporozhye Region Kamensk-Dneprovsk District have voted against 
the utilization of the sixth block of the Zaporozhye Nuclear 
Power Station. A total of 38 percent of voters voted for it 
during a referendum held along with the presidential and local 
elections in Ukraine. 
  Voters were asked whether it was reasonable to switch on the 
sixth block before a law on nuclear energy was adopted. The 
ballot papers also included a question on whether a storage 
facility for exhaust nuclear fuel could be built in the region. 
  An INTERFAX correspondent reports that 32 percent of voters 
were in favor of such a facility for exhausted nuclear fuel and 
63 percent were against. A total of 68 percent of the voters 
registered in the region took part in the referendum. 
  This referendum was initiated by the District Council. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

