<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shakhray Says Elections Could Be Delayed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shakhray Says Elections Could Be Delayed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2706154694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1322 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2706154694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The proposal on putting off parliamentary and 
presidential elections could be implemented by prolonging the 
Pact on Civic Accord, Vice Premier Sergey Shakhray told Interfax. 
  In his opinion, such a move would appease a wide spectrum of 
political forces, including the opposition which he believes 
would support the idea of postponing elections in the absence of 
a realistic contender to Boris Yeltsin and in hope that such a 
contender will at some point emerge in the ranks of the 
opposition. 
  He also said that the Civic Accord Pact was "a document 
based 
on a certain balance of political interests and forces." "Given 
political will, it can easily be prolonged by amending the 
Constitution and by prolonging the powers of all branches of 
authority," he said. 
  He welcomed the political forces' newly acquired skill for 
coming to terms with one another, but noted that in the current 
complicated situation, early elections could also help to ease 
political tensions. 
  He also expressed the opinion that the proposal to put off 
elections was the Russian political elite's attempt to prolong 
its term in office. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

