<F P=100> CAUCASUS </F>
<F P=101> Armenia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Aide Calls on Karabakh Leader To Attend Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Aide Calls on Karabakh Leader To Attend Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2706194794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1907 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2706194794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tigran Liloyan] </F>
  [Text] Yerevan June 27 TASS -- "A separate meeting between 
the Armenian and Azeri leaders would be senseless since the 
comprehensive settlement of the Karabakh conflict can be reached 
only by the three sides involved Armenia, Azerbaijan and 
Nagorno-Karabakh," said Levon Zurabyan, the Armenian president's 
aide and his acting press secretary. "If such a meeting takes 
place, it should be attended by the Nagorno-Karabakh leader 
Robert Kocharyan," the aide said. 
  The representative of the Armenian president positively 
assessed the results of today's talks in Yerevan conducted by 
the Russian president's special envoy, Vladimir Kazimirov. The 
Armenian president's aide pointed out the importance of such 
working meetings for the clarification of positions assumed by 
the sides on the Karabakh settlement. 

</TEXT>

