<F P=100> CAUCASUS </F>
<F P=101> Armenia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yerevan Reports Cease-Fire Violations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yerevan Reports Cease-Fire Violations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2706160694 Yerevan Radio Yerevan in Azeri 1330 GMT 27 Jun 
94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2706160694 </F>
<F P=104>  Yerevan Radio Yerevan </F>
<F P=105>  Azeri </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Dear listeners, we now present a report on the 
latest situation in the Nagorno-Karabakh Republic [NKR] and the 
border between Armenia and Azerbaijan. 
  The latest reports from the NKR have confirmed that no 
incident has occurred in the confrontation areas. The sides 
have been trying not to allow any incident which may create a 
new tension in the region. In general, the cease-fire agreement 
is being heeded. The situation in the front line areas is 
peaceful, that is, not taking into account the shooting by 
Azerbaijan's military units from time to time. In view of that, 
we hope that the peaceful situation will not be temporary and 
that a result will be achieved through the talks that are held 
at various levels to convince the two sides to end the 
confrontation. 
  Regrettably, a stable situation has not been established on 
the border between Armenia and Azerbaijan. The reason for that 
state of affairs is the frequent shooting from Azerbaijan in the 
direction of various settlements in Armenia. Azerbaijan's 
military units have fired mainly on Armenia's Idzhevanskiy, 
Tavushskiy, Noyemberyanskiy, and Araratskiy Rayons. Other areas 
also have been fired on. It must be stressed for the sake of 
justice that the Armenian side has refrained from returning the 
fire in several cases. 
  The Armenian Ministry of Defense Information Service has 
disclosed that Azerbaijan's military units fired on several 
border towns in Noyemberyanskiy Rayon with various types of arms 
last night. The Armenian side did not return the fire. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

