<F P=100> Azerbaijan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Aliyev Supports Inviting Iran, Turkey to Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Aliyev Supports Inviting Iran, Turkey to Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2706165794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1500 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2706165794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" feature: Compiled by </F>
Nikolay Zherebtsov, Andrey Petrovskiy; edited by Vladimir 
Shishlin] 
  [Text] Azerbaijani President Heydar Aliyev believes 
inviting neighboring Iran and Turkey to take part in 
negotiations on Nagorno-Karabakh would be a positive factor. 
Aliyev was speaking on Sunday as he received the special 
Russian presidential envoy Vladimir Kazimirov at talks on 
Nagorno-Karabakh in Baku. 
  The Russian diplomat arrived in the Azerbaijani capital from 
Iran, where he had had consultations with that country's foreign 
ministry officials. He said consultations with the Turkish 
Foreign Ministry were due to be held shortly. 
  President Aliyev would like the current cease-fire to be 
used 
to speed up the process of negotiations. At the same time 
Aliyev said that Azerbaijan's conditions for a final political 
agreement remained unchanged -- Armenian armed detachments must 
be withdrawn from captured territories and Azerbaijani refugees 
returned to their homes. 
  President Aliyev promised that supply lines would be 
restored 
and the safety of Nagorno-Karabakh's Armenians as citizens of 
Azerbaijan ensured. President Aliyev said that a discussion of 
Nagorno-Karabakh's future status would depend on the 
comprehensive implementation of all those requirements. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

