<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Intelligence Service Chief Visits Chisinau </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russian Intelligence Service Chief Visits Chisinau </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2706144894 Chisinau BASAPRESS in English 2110 GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2706144894 </F>
<F P=104>  Chisinau BASAPRESS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Chisinau BASAPRESS, 24/6/1994 -- The chief of the 
Federal Intelligence Service of Russia, Sergey Stepashin [name 
as received], arrived today in Chisinau. Sources from the 
Moldovan Ministry of National Security stated to BASAPRESS that 
the Russian dignitary is in Chisinau to sign an agreement of 
cooperation between the security services of both states. The 
draft agreement stipulates the coordination of joint activities 
in combating terrorism, smuggling, drug business, and illegal 
armament trade. The parties also intend to come to an agreement 
concerning joining forces in combating the illegal immigration 
of citizens of underdeveloped countries to Western Europe, by 
using the territories of Russia and Moldova as transit stations. 
The same sources announced to BASAPRESS that Sergey Stepashin 
will stay in Moldova two days and will meet President Mircea 
Snegur and Premier Andrei Sangheli. Stepashin also intends to 
pay a visit to Tiraspol. No terrorist acts were committed this 
year in Moldova. In 1993, the Moldovan frontier guards 
prevented the attempts of dozens of illegal immigrants to 
traverse Moldova. 

</TEXT>

